In article <8904111857.AA16683@decwrl.dec.com> docsvs%docs.DEC@DECWRL.DEC.COM (Karen J. Norteman, APO2/C15; DTN 289-1623) writes:

> I didn't have the blasted danglie more than 24 hours before my phone started
> ringing.  (I'm not kidding!)  The first conversation went something like this
> (my paraphrase): "Ariel old-buddy-old-pal, now that you're a Silver Crescent
> you WILL nominate So-and-So, won't you?!"  Many subsequent conversations
> followed the same path.  I can't go to an event without someone
> coming up to me and giving the same "old-buddy-old-pal" speech.  

Good my lady Ariel, I sympathize with your problem.  I suspect it is
not uncommon, especially in the more remote parts of any Kingdom,
where the number of members of the higher orders is small.

On one hand, you've got to expect this sort of thing.  One of your
duties as a Companion of an order is to be aware of who is doing
valuable work, and who ought to receive recognition.  People bring
their recommendations to you because you DO have a somewhat bigger
say.  It is not for nothing that many scrolls refer to companionship
in an order, and "the rights and duties pertaining thereunto".
                                 ^^^^^^

However, I think part of your problem may be that many people in your
area don't understand that ANYONE can (and should!) make award
recommendations to the Crown.  Tell them so: If they all write letters
to the Crown, the award is much more likely to be given than if they
leave it to you.  Thank them for their thoughts, and tell them you
will keep them in mind.  

	Arval
