Message-Id: <8904131424.AA14342@decwrl.dec.com>
From: iannuzzo%mosaic.DEC@decwrl.dec.com (Catherine T., DTN 226-2401, LJ02/H4)
Date: 13 Apr 89 10:21
Subject: gay monarchs

To the gentles of the Rialto,

Goodness... I miss a few digests and all of a sudden I see this storm 
over whether or not gay monarchs should be able to choose same-sex 
consorts.  Anxiety about this kind of thing was something of a major 
issue for me when I joined the society.  I am rather unlikely at this 
point to end up having to choose a consort in a crown tourney, but 
nonetheless, the almost overwhelming heterosexism of the society can
make someone like myself a little uncomfortable. 

Since heterosexuals are used to seeing themselves and their lifestyles 
as "normal" and "natural", few are aware of the ironic double standard 
applied to homosexuals.  We are allowed to exist (at least among the 
more tolerant) as long as we don't "flaunt it".  However, ever scadian 
dance, every tourney filled with knights graced with their lord's or 
lady's favors, every court, and every little social interaction flavored 
with friendly flirtatiousness flaunts, extols, and enforces heterosexual
courtship and mating rituals.  It is impossible to avoid being inundated 
by it.

For a homosexual, the smallest things can be fraught with real and 
imaginary perils that the average heterosexual hasn't a glimmer of.
Maybe my story of "what-to-wear" might illustrate the point a little 
bit.  [apologies for telling part of my how-I-met-the-sca tale over again.]
I went through a lot of trauma at my first major activity (which
happened to be Pennsic) deciding what to wear (since you are what you
wear, to a large extent, in sca-land).  In mundane existence it is possible
to choose a non-commitally androgynous style, but in these current
middle ages it is much harder.  What one wears declares one's role, and
the binding between gender and role behavior is very, very tight.  Many
people have trouble making a distinction between maleness and
"masculine" behavior and femaleness and "feminine" behavior in the best
of times, somehow assuming that one proceeds automatically from the
other as if it were ordained by <ultimate being of your choice>.  And of
course one of the biggest assumptions of such behavior is an orientation
toward the opposite sex. I have no taste for fitting into a "feminine"
role generally, and at the beginning the thought of wearing a gown,
being called "my lady" by chivalrous gentlemen, and <gasp> being 
expected to dance with men, filled me with panic.  At the same time, I
was unsure if it was safe to wear male garb or what that would mean.  

I hit upon a very period solution -- I went as a nun.  It declared me a
non-player in the default mating game and made me feel fairly
comfortable -- except after a few days or so of 90 degree heat in a
black habit. I ended up stitching up a tunic by hand and throwing it
over my chemise to be cooler.  I suddenly became a "lady".  I had the
interesting reaction of feeling weak and vulnerable and "in disguise"
(which may seem like an odd thing for someone who loves to run around in
medieval outfits to say, but it has to do with some kind of fundamental
misrepresentation of self).  Being single, I also realized that if there
were any other females out there who might be players in the same mating 
game that interested me, they'd probably never know I was available.
And shy as I am, I do like to play the game too, once in a while.
I realized more than I ever had before how those of us who break with 
our fundamental role expectations in the matter of sexual orientation 
often give off "gender-bending" clues (pink polo shirts for men, 
flattops for women, etc) in order to find each other.  I finally worked
up an outfit for court that consisted of a borrowed doublet, some 
mundane pants rigged up as venetians, and a zippy little feathered hat.
I looked very Genoese, one lady told me.  At that point I realized I was 
emotionally comfortable with myself.  And on my last day, when I was 
running around in a tunic (sans chemise), with baggy pants and one of 
those very butch leather belts favored by the stick jock classes, a lady
finally expressed to me her loneliness for the evening, but it was 
too late.  [I would like to state that I am not a lustful lesbian who 
joined the sca to meet hot babes in kirtles -- I am actually a rather 
shy and quiet individual, and quite respectful of the fact that almost 
all other women will never be other than friendly acquaintances, or at 
best objects of unrequited devotion].

Anyway, that might all seem like a rambly and pointless story, but I 
hope it illustrates a little bit how when one doesn't belong to the 
default group, one's "difference" becomes very much a burning, every day 
issue fraught with questions of one's true identity.  I won't even get 
into the gyrations I've gone through trying to choose a name and 
persona, or the hand-wringing I went through when I went to my first 
dress-up dance and worried about whether I would be able to dance with 
ladies and if that would be ok and what they would think of it and what 
I should answer when the first person I spoke to asked if he should call 
me "my lord" or "my lady".  I am grateful to say that I live in a fine 
barony, and that much of what I agonized over in private seems to have 
turned out to be a non-issue.  Most people admire my garb, and there are 
enough partnerless ladies out there that I can usually dance
without it being any kind of earth-shattering issue, and I've learned 
not to mind dancing on the distaff side with men whom I think of as 
friends.  But it is worth mentioning that these things are issues for 
me, and for a heterosexual they never come up.

Of course it bothers me that a heterosexual has the option of choosing
his or her beloved as a consort, while that option is categorically
denied to me and my kind.  I want to fight for a lady, and live out my
own chivalrous fantasies.  Why, in this land of make believe, is that
denied to me?  In a world where one runs the risk of being assaulted on 
the street for looking like a dyke or a faggot, such injustices are 
certainly minor.  But they are injustices all the same -- little 
irritations that add to the dis-integration many of us experience in 
keeping our loves and a fundamental part of who we are separate from
the rest of our lives.  I'm not sure anyone else can understand the kind of 
psychological mutilation it is to have to have to deny oneself in that 
way.  The rest of you get to carry on your courtships in 
public, get approval and celebrations for your mating, get to write 
songs, poems, plays, and great literature about your attachments, have
your families treated as sacred institutions whose bonds are holy and
good, while the rest of us have to hide whom we love and who we are, and
defend ourselves against accusations of shame, sin, and illegality.  I
don't like it, and I don't like anything that contributes to
legitimizing this assault against our humanity. 

I consider the "not period" arguments to be so much rationalization for 
the way things are.  Much of the sca is "not period" -- we are far from 
being a faithful recreation of medieval society.  What we choose to 
allow or not allow that is "not period" is an indication of our values.
Certainly there were many homosexual sovereigns in the period, although 
admittedly most of them married consorts of the opposite sex out of
political duty and kept their lovers in the shadows on the side.  Lots 
of Spanish Moors pretended to be Christians, too.  The hatred and 
intolerance vented on Jews, Muslims, and women during the period are very
authentic, but is at least considered impolite to openly express in the
world today.  I doubt anyone would consider saying it isn't period to
have a Jewish sovereign, for example.  But because hatred and
intolerance toward homosexuals are still completely valid in the world
today, and the religions that once felt it a holy duty to kill Jews and
Muslims and old women still feel it is ok to dehumanize homosexuals, we
can come up with good rational-sounding excuses for why gay men and
lesbians ought to be stuffed into the closet and have the doors nailed
shut by the good people of the sca.  The attitude doesn't surprise me at
all, but I wish that it wouldn't try to hide behind a seemingly pious
and rational facade.  Discrimination on the basis of whom I choose to 
love is unfair and it hurts, and whether or not such unfairness is 
period or expedient changes it not one whit.

Yours,

Jehanne du Lac du Flamant,
Barony of Carolingia

