Lords and Ladies of the Rialto,

The subject of Richard the Lionheart has reminded me of something I encountered
long ago in another place.  People willing to act as contacts for the SCA had
their phone numbers listed under the name "Richard Lionheart".  That way, if
you were in a strange place, all you had to do was look up Lionheart in the
phone book to find a contact person.  It's free, too, because the phone company
asks you how you want your name listed in the phone book.  A second listing
with a second name costs money.  It has the added benefit of allowing you to
screen callers.  If they ask for "Mr. Lionheart" you know they're a stranger to
you.  That means they're either SCA, or want to sell you something.

I think it would be good to encourage this practice.  It would make it easier
for people to find other SCA people.  We might expand the role a bit for such
peole to be hospitallers.  For example, a SCA person is traveling.  Their car
breaks down in a strange city.  They have no idea who's a reputable dealer or
not, they're stranded without any way to get to a motel, the local "Lionheart"
could help then out.  Such Lionhearts would be providing a useful service with
very little effort on their part.

In fact, the whole idea of Hospitallers is a good one.  A few years ago Aaron
the Black, a member of Saint John's Ambulance in Canada (one  of the surviving
services offered by the real Hospitallers) started a group of Hospitallers.  He
got permission from the mundane Hospitallers to use their device (white Maltese
cross on a black field) and began providing emergency services.  (He was
paramedic so he acted as a chirurgeon, but he also offered up spare sleeping
space. He was also a former boy scout troop leader who had old boy scout tents).

At Pennsic on more than one occasion bad weather has rendered many people
homeless, wet, and hungry with no dry place to sleep, no dry clothes to change
into, and no edible food.  The Dark Horde has done handsome service by feeding,
warming, and housing lots of these people.  Seems to me emergency
accomodations of this sort could be an adjunct to the services of the
chirurgeons.

I'd appreciate any comments on this subject, also, I've lost contact with
Aaron.  If anybody knows where he is or how to reach him, I'd appreciate it.
His mundane name is Bob Pine.

Yours in Hospitality,
Awilda Halfdane
Bright Hills, Atlantia
