Greetings!

First things first:  I *love* hearing about all these "And Now for Something
*COMPLETELY* Different" Tourneys!  More, please!!

Regarding alternate personae, and without respect to opinion:  everyone seems
to be overlooking what registering lots of different names equally (as opposed
to one primary name/persona) would do the the Registry and their work load!
They ain't got but 24 hours in a day, y'know!

There's also the Heralds and Scribes:  one of the purposes of having a primary
name is to permit people preparing awards and their scrolls to have a uniform
name to put them in!  It's also useful for people making awards
recommendations, and even decisions.  One primary name means less confusion as
to who is being referred to.  I mean, picture it:  the Crown figures these 42
Letters of Recommendation are for 6 different people, when it's really only
gentle known by 6 names!  No, thanks all the same!

By the way:  it was *years* before the College of Arms unbent enough to allow
the registration of alternate personae _via_ badges, and there is a limit to
how many of these you can register (I thinks it's eight, but I'm not sure).
And, *that* was a begrudging compromise.

About Lady Ariel of Caer Myrddin's problem with her Silver Crescent:  I
wholeheartedly agree with Ellisig Flakkingskvinne.  When anyone gives you that
kind of problem about *any* award, your first response should be:  "Have you
written a letter of recommendation for them?"  Nine times out of 10, the
answer will be "No."  To which you respond by politely pointing out that
without letters of rec., how is the Order to know who to consider, or have
documentation to back up their decisions?

If the answer is "yes," refer them to the Crown and/or the Principal of the
Order.  All kinds of screw-ups are possible; and in the event the gentle in
question was considered and not voted in, then the Crown or Principal are in
the best position to field such questions.

Either way, try not to let it get to you.  If you keep smiling, giving
consistent answers, and deferring, this too shall pass!


