A while ago someone asked for advice about how to make fighting more
interesting for non-participants.  A similar subject came up at the planning
meeting for Crusade of the Bright Rose (official war practice for Atlantia and
East theis year).

Non-fighters don't have to watch fighting.  It is, after, not the be all and end
all of the SCA.  One period entertainment that I like is for the less physical
members of the Society: Chess.

Played with medeival variants, it can be a lot of fun.  It is especially fun
trying to watch experienced chess players trying to figure out how to cope with
unfamiliar rules.   A while back I co-autocratted an event where we had a
Chocolate Chess Tourney.  Now chocolate is out of period-but it's such a little
sin for so much fun.

At the lower levels palyers played medieval variants.  For the finale, the
 four finalists played Four Seasons chess with the chocolate pieces of four
 different colors. They got to eat the pieces they captured. 

Each player sat at his corner with half the usual number of pieces and
wondered how in the heck he was going to play.  It attracted a large crowd of
spectators (an unusual phenomenon in its own right) all of whom were offering
excellent advice, such as "Capture the white piece, George!  I want to taste it!"

Alas, pieces were devoured faster than strategy progressed, and the game was
declared a draw.  The spectators demanded that I do it again. And  I might.


Yours in service to non-fighting fun,
