Message-Id: <8904111130.AA06852@ceridwen.sics.se>
Subject: cotss (Consort of the Same Sex)
Date: Tue, 11 Apr 89 13:30:24 +0200
From: annika@sics.se


I wonder if my opinion hasn't been voiced before...

Your love can be your consort.
A friend of yours can be your consort.
You consort must be of the opposite sex.

These facts lead to an inconsistency. As usual, when solving an inconsistency,
you must choose preferences. What is most important: the rule that your 
consort must be of the opposite sex, or the rule that your mate can be
your consort ? There are other cases when your love can't be your consort
 - if your love is not in the SCA at all ! And conversely, if your love do
not fight, you must choose a fighter among your friends (or fight yourself).

Somebody compared this to the rule that prohibited women from fighting. But
the rule that women weren't allowed to fight EXCLUDED people from partaking
in some activities in the SCA. The rule that your consort must be of the 
opposite sex doesn't exclude anybody to fight for crown - he or she must
simply 'play the game' and choose a consort of the opposite sex. It had been
possible to solve the problem with women fighters in a similar manner by
requiring women to fight under a male persona (although this would certainly 
cause problems with the 'consort of opposite sex' rule :-). I guess that one 
of the reasons this solution wasn't chosen, was that there were enough evidence
that women fighters were, in fact, period. (It is also period to be gay, so I 
cannot see any problem with an openly - or almost openly - gay persona. There
are several interesting ways such a persona could be used.)

Now, there might be another reason for allowing consorts of the same sex:
the idea that the society should be a non-prejudiced organization, without
any discrimination whatsoever, and that its rules should not only be 
non-discriminating, but also be impossible to interpret as discriminating. I 
don't have very much arguments against this idea, only that however beautiful 
it is, this is NOT the purpose of the society. The purpose of the society is 
to provide an organization for people who want to study and reenact 'very old 
times'. I think that the society should not exclude anyone from partaking  - 
regardless of race, sex, disabilities, sexual preferences, religion or
whatever you can think of. For example, I see this principle as a valid reason
for prohibiting a mass to be the main activity at an event. But as long as
this principle isn't violated, I think the society's first concern is to
keep the reenactment reasonably truthful.

Also, we DO have members with views and beliefs like Lord Williams. I do not 
think we need to violate their beliefs either - or exclude them from some 
activities -  as long as their beliefs do not exclude someone else from
partaking in SCA activities.

Putting in my two kronor (approximately a quarter) worth,

Katherin Jonsdotter,
Annika Waern
annika@sics.se


