Some gentles on the net have given a translation of the mottoe of the
Order of the Garter which sounds a bit strange to me.

The mottoe (or, what the King said) is:
"Honi soit qui mal y pense"

The translation I have seen on the net is "Evil to him who thinks evil."

In my book, this is incorrect. The translation should be:
"Shame on him who thinks badly thereof", 
meaning "shame on you, milords, if you think that anything wrong
has been done here (referring to the dropping of the garter).

I will quote a bit about the Garter from a book called "Awards of
Honour". I have only some photocopies from this book, taken many
years ago, and stupidly I never noted the author's name.

"With respect to its origin, there appears to have been two popular but
legendary versions. Although the exact date of its foundation must be
regarded as uncertain, Seldon and Froissart concur in fixing the date of
institution to the 18th year of Edward III, when at the battle of Crecy,
the King ordered his garter to be displayed as the signal for the onset.
Other chroniclers (probably French) attributed its origin to a frivolous
incident associated with the Countess of Salisbury...whose garter, they
allege, fell off while dancing, and in rebuke of the levity this incident
aroused, the King uttered the words which were sunsequently adopted as 
the motto of the Order."

The book then goes on to quote a lengthy refutal of both these stories
as unhistoric, by someone called "Pote" whom I suspect may be an official
historian of the Order. I don't know what to believe; on the one hand,
the official historians may have wanted to cover up or explain away
any "frivolous" or un-Victorian origin of the Order - on the other hand,
it is perfectly possible that the romantic stories are just legends that
caught the public imagination and have little to do with reality.

