     I would like to begin by pointing out that since males have pretty
completely dominated Crown (and even Coronet) Tournaments in the past,
and are likely to continue to do so in the future, then same-sex royal
couples would almost certainly be male, and so if we permitted them
females would be unfairly discriminated against.  The narrow-mindedly
open-minded (meaning those who can't stand even to think of anything
that doesn't seem "perfectly" egalitarian) may stop reading right now,
as this argument should be enough to convince them.  Anyone who really
is open-minded, and isn't just trying very hard to fake it, is welcome
to read on.

     I see absolutely nothing wrong with homosexual royalty.  Probably
many if not most Kingdoms have already had both bisexual and homosexual
monarchs in the past anyway.  I'd be upset (and also surprised) if I
found that anyone had ever been prevented from ruling an SCA Kingdom
because of their sexual preference.
     But I am completely opposed to the idea that we should permit same-
sex royal couples, and I don't see that there is anything the least bit
homophobic about this.  Of course, the current policy means that people
can't reign together with their lovers, or even virtual spouses, of the
same sex, but that's beside the point.  One's "Consort" isn't supposed
to be a spouse, or a lover, or even a girlfriend - or a boyfriend.  That
is neither required nor expected anywhere in the Known World.
     As for the argument that we should allow such royal couples on
general principles, to support the right of homosexuals to have their
relationships accepted by society, that at least has the advantage of
having some basis in reality.  But I think we ought to accept the fact
that some of the things done in the SCA aren't supposed to be symbolic
of pure egalitarianism, enlightenment, or reason.  Take fighting for
example.  If SCA people really were the rabid warmongers that they so
often act like ;-) I wouldn't touch the group with an eleven-foot pole.
Similarly, our royalty aren't supposed to represent our attitudes.  If
they represent anything at all, what they represent is not attitudes but
archetypes.  And I'd rather not try to evict all the archetypes from my
head, or get them all mixed up with each other, in the name of equality.
     I simply can't buy the idea of a same-sex royal couple, no matter
how cheap it comes, ;-) and I don't see any reason why I should have to.
It seems to me like saying that equal rights for women means men can't
lead when dancing.  It's a silly, trivial complaint when compared with
real unfairness.  And before anyone tells me that women might have equal
rights if only they got to lead dances as often as they followed, I'd
like to remind people that English country dancing gives approximate
equality to both sexes/roles, and it was very popular in the seventeenth
century, which as we all know was a golden age of egalitarianism. ;-)
"Equal Rights in Dancing, and Burn the Witches!"
     In a nutshell (and I'm sure some people think I belong in one ;-) )
I think we should try to take care of the important things, such as
the right of homosexuals not to be murdered by heterosexuals, before we
try to enforce such questionable rights as the right of a homosexual
couple to be the "King" and "Queen" of an SCA Kingdom, in persona.

