In article <7807@pucc.Princeton.EDU> SSKATZ@pucc.Princeton.EDU writes:
>A question to the brewers of the Rialto.
>We are planning a Medieval Tavern on May 4, and I would like to brew
>some mead for the event.  Is there time?  Will the stuff ferment quickly
>(and tastily) enough if I start, say, April 16?  Also, it is very
>difficult to get yeast of any sort around here.  Is it possible to do
>without?
>        In service,
>                Yaakov HaMizrachi


     I have found that the only thing that produces a drinkable liquid 
in less than a month is a good malt liquor.  A malt liquor is simply a
honey mead that has had some malt extract (malt sugar, or maltose) added
to the must.  The addition of the malt sugar speeds fermentation (which,
incidentally, makes it much less likely that some foreign yeast or other
microbial culture can get a foothold in your mix).  If you use malt that
has been flavored with hops, you get a nicely flavored drink, which is
potable at one week, fairly good at two, and possibly quite good at
three.  This last year at Pennsic, I got a 3-week old Cinnamon Malt
Liquor approved by the Brewer's and Vintner's Guild.  Of course, it
*was* a rather exceptional batch, as far as malt liquors go, but. . .

     I measure my malt liquors by the can (I use an empty can of malt
extract, even when not using canned malt), so I can't tell you the
exact proportions of malt and honey to the water (I usually make 5 gallon
batches), but if you're interested and send me a note, I'll go figure 
it out.  Oh, and I use Montrachet wine yeast for the malt liquors, and
flavor with anything from ginger to cinnamon and cloves.  This is the
easiest way I know of to make a potable "quick drink."  If you make 
enough of it, too, it can serve to keep your hands off of the rest of
the aging "good stuff" that you've been saving for posterity, or the
next Pennsic War.

     And if you have trouble finding yeast locally, I'll mail you some.


