     Greetings all gentlefolk of the Rialto, Chelidon o Gaerddrych sends
greetings and hopes of fair fortunes, unto one and all. . .

     To begin with, I would like to mention that Charles ffoulkes 
excellent book, _The armourer and his craft from the XIth to the XVIth
century_, is back in print from Dover Publications, after I believe being
out of print since 1912 or so.  The only other copies I have seen have
been 1912 editions in various libraries.  The book is an anachronist's
dream, with excerpts from period armorer's bills (the monetary kind), 
mail-making methods, barding diagrams, documents from the records of The
Armourer's Company, London (1322) and other primary sources, descriptions
of changes in armor standards in response to various historical and technical
developments (the most obvious of which being the use of gunpowder), an
excellent glossary of armor and armoring terms, etc etc etc.  Please excuse
my verbiage, I wax enthusiastic.  It's one of those books I've always wanted
my own copy of.  Now if the price of the complete facsimile copies in color
of the Book of Kells would only come down, say, a few hundred dollars. . .

     Now some comments on recent posts:

     Steffan ap Cennydd made mention some time back of the term "Spiriti
vini rectificati" as a medieval equivalent for "Everclear."  I hve recently
run across a survival of the phrase, in the form of a bottle of "Spirytus
Rectifikowany" given to me by a friend who brought it over from Poland.  And
the stuff is labeled 95% alcohol content.  Upon small tastes, it seems to
be flavored with peppercorns and mace.  Suffice it to say that it is among
the most unpleasant stuff I'v ever tasted in my life.  I know quite a few
"professional" SCA drinkers who swear this is the *only* stuff they WILL NOT
TOUCH.  It does, however, flame quite nicely, but the remaining liquid then
smells and tastes like melted plastic.  This drink was quickly christened,
"The Flaming Asshole," partially due to a bad pun on "Rectalfied Spirits,"
and partly because you'd have to be one to actually drink the stuff.  Ahem.

     My addition to the mead discussion:

     I've found that Montrachet wine yeast does a good job if you want to
produce a fairly dry (i.e., most of the sugar changed to alcohol) mead.  I
have managed to produce a sweeter mead with Montrachet, but only when making
a Black Mead (8 lbs of blackcurrants and 4lbs of honey, along with some
grapes in 2 lbs of water, with some extras), which has a great deal of
sugar in the must, or other high-sugar mixes.  The black mead turned out
very much like a good Madiera wine, slightly sweet and *very* strong.  I
get the impression that particular batch of yeasties died happy, i.e., met
with their alcohol tolerence level. . .
      A quick mead-making story, that happened about two months ago:

      I was having one of the once-monthly bardic circles over at my place,
and had made up a large bowl of wassail for the event.  Incidentally, I
had also started two batches of mead the day before.  One of the batches,
a braggart (intermediate stage between mead and ale, honey and malt, fermented
with an ale yeast), was still sitting on the stove in a covered stew pot,
with a large label, "BR02  2/18/89" stuck to the front.  Inside was my
happily-fermenting braggart, with a thick yeast-scum floating on top of the
just-barely-fermented mix.  Whilst I was in the basement, a friend of mine
who shall remain nameless to protect the guilty (but some of you might know
him as Feather), apparently thinking that this was one of the Drinks of the
Day, dipped his cup into the stuff and took a deep draught.  His comment,
along with what was apparently an indecribable facial expression, was,
"Uh, Chelidon always has such *interesting* drinks."  He did, however, take
a second cup.
     When informed about a month later what he had actually been drinking
(to explain any symptoms of bouyancy he may have been feeling as he
fermented), he laughed a bit with the rest of us, then, suddenly grew
ashen-white.  He stumbled a bit in his speech, but managed to stammer out,
"so THAT explains the doctor's diagnosis.  I TOLD her it wasn't my fault!"
You see, it seems that Feather had, not three weeks previous, been diagnosed
as having a yeast infection, and had been receiving much grief from his SO. . .

     On the subject of unusual tournaments:          

     I am not certain if this has ever been done before, but if so, I don't  
remember hearing of it.  The game is Combat Sheep Rugby, and the rules are as
follows:  fighters are divided into four clans, each clan standing at a corner
of the field, next to a clan banner.  In the middle of the field is a sheep.
(a saw-horse with a couple of 4x4s slung underneath, wrapped in sheepskin.
For you Vikings out there, the sheep  is NOT anatomically correct)  At the
signal to start, a melee begins,  with the object being to grab the sheep
(which is heavy and bulky enough to keep the carrier from using any weapons
effectively), and carry it around two poles in the middle of the field, then
back to your own clan banner.  The sheep is really too bulky to be used
effectively as a shield, so your only hope of getting it is to have your
fellow clansmen form a protective wall around you as you carry the sheep 
around the field (that, or do away with all of the opposing teams and be 
the last clan with live people on the field).  
     
     We'll be running this tourney at the Celtic Clan War and Cattle Raid
Beltaine Bash, to be held on Saturday, April 29 at the Bellefonte KOA
campground in central Pennsylvania, along with many other Celtic-theme
events, contests, etc.  For more info, check April's Pikestaff, or email
hoffman@gondor.cs.psu.edu or hoffman%psuvaxg@psuvax1.bitnet.  There.  That
takes care of my plug for the day.

     Finally, on the issue of barons and baronies:

     Before coming to the East Kingdom, I was originally involved with
The Barony of the Western Seas, in Caid (mundanely the State of Hawaii).
Barons are chosen there on a biannual basis.  Once a year, a fighter's
tournament is held, with the winning fighter being Baron or Baroness for
6 mo. On the alternate 6-month periods, an arts competition is held, with
the Baron or Baroness being selected for excellence in a series of arts
contests.  Is this such an unusual system, or is it commonly done elsewhere?
Were one looking to revamp the Kingdom Crown Tournaments (I am not), this
model might be one to examine.

