RE: The Order of the Garter:
 
The way I heard the Order of the Garter story, it was, specifically
the Countess of Salisbury who dropped her garter, and Edward I who
picked it up, saying Honi Soit Qui Mal Y Pense (Evil to him who
thinks Evil).  The garter clearly identified the Countess as a leader
in the Old Religion, and Edward, being a quick thinking sort, quickly
extended the King's protection lest the Countess get into trouble with
the (state) religious authorities.
 
The rest of what I heard coincides with Samuel Bassett's account about
the numbers in the order, etc.  The Order of the Garter is still
considered one of the most prestigious.  Winston Churchill refused a
peerage, but allowed as how he would consider a knighthood in the
Order (which he received in due course).
 
For a good supply of neat stories, try to get hold of Margaret Murray's
The Divine King in England.  (Margaret Murray was an Egyptologist who
lost her reputation when she published this book.)
 
RE: SCA Favours
 
Medieval practice has been well described
already.  To add my two cents on SCA practices, favours can be
given for several reasons including serious "I fight for your honour"
favours and friendship favours.
 
I used to give my favour to a female friend, when she was fighting,
as a sign of my support of, and confidence in her.
She was deeply involved with her lord, whose favour she also
carried next to her person at all times.  The one had nothing to do with
the other, and all parties knew that.
 
The knight in my household carries my favour.  He and his lady
offered this honour to me several years ago when I had no lord.  He wears
this with his other favours when fighting-except when he enters Crown
Tourney where he wears only the favour of his lady wife, as is proper.
One of the fighters in our household carries a favour from
me in the household colours.  I made a token for our baronial harper,
at his request.
I have, on occasion, given a token to a fighter for the duration of
a tourney, as a sign of encouragement and friendship.
(Being a Baroness provides lots of extra opportunities
for embroidery.)
 
It seems to me that the giving and receiving of favours can mean many
things.  Some of the things we call favours in the SCA might medievally
have been called something else (gifts, tokens, etc.).
The important part about SCA favours is that both the donor and the
recipient agreed on what a particular favour means.
 
