Date: 10 Apr 89 15:37:59 GMT
From: lts!amanda@uunet.uu.net  (Amanda Walker)
Subject: Personas, Same-sex royalty, courtesy, etc...
Message-Id: <1106@lts.UUCP>

Good gentles, I'd like to start by saying "Poo-Bah!" to everyone who
has been participating in the somewhat rambling discussion about
same-sex royalty and so on.  The courtesy that has been shown by all,
even in disagreement, does the Society a lot of credit.  I think that
the clash between medieval and modern attitudes, as well the contrast
between a person and their persona, points out some important things
about how the Society. 

Saying that people and their personas are separate both is and is not
true. 

No, the Society is certainly not "real life." It's not even a
particularly accurate recreation of medieval "real life." At it's best
(which can be very fine indeed), though, it does interact with "real
life." For example, the SCA has taught me a lot over the years about
courtesy and service, which are values not often taken seriously in
the whole at large, but which I have found ways to work into my
mundane life that I wouldn't have found if it had not been for my
experience with the SCA.  My persona is not my life, but it is
nonetheless part of who I am, and thus the SCA is part of my life, and
an important one at that.  When I go to an event, there is a sense in
which I'm play-acting, but it's play-acting with serious overtones. 

Likewise, when I'm sitting at my drafting table working on a scroll in
fourteenth-century French style, I am not play-acting.  I am in fact
creating an illuminated page, and the skills (not to mention the time
and energy I have put into developing them), the time involved, and
the delight I get in seeing it presented in court are very real.
Granted, I am not a period scribe, producing period scrolls--for one
thing, I don't think period scribes sat in air-conditioned apartments
in jeans and a sweater using Winsor-Newton designer's gouache and
listening to Carmina Burana on the CD player while they illuminated
:-).  Even so, that doesn't make what I do entirely an act, either.  I
am not a fourteenth-century nun, but I am nonetheless a scribe. 

A similar thing can be said about musicians playing at a feast.  Yes,
a harp may be strung with modern strings, and may have been tuned with
an electronic tuner, but the musician does in fact play for a crowded
feast hall, but an appreciative comment from their Majesties and
table-pounding from the populace still make it all worthwhile. 

I imagine the same can be said for fighters.  I mean, nobody gets
killed (and hopefully, no one even gets hurt), but scrambling through
muddy woods in armor fighting for your kingdom is not entirely a game
in the same sense as, say, Monopoly or bridge...  The weapons and
wounds may not be real, but there's still something important
happening. 

And this, I think, is really what the Society comes down to.  We
recreate, not the Middle Ages, but those parts of the Middle Ages that
we find important, and that are missing from modern life.  The fact
that they are missing does not make them unreal.  Rather, it makes the
chance to take part in them in a friendly environment with 12,000
other people all that much more precious. 

<short pause while I wrestle this message back to its original topic>

Unfortunately, the true strength of the Society, the investment that
we make of ourselves in order to make this whole thing work, is also
one of its weaknesses.  In short, taking it seriously has its good
points and its bad points.  On the good side, the SCA could not exist
without the investment that all of us put into it.  On the bad side,
it means that our activities and our personas are a much closer
reflection of who we are than they would be if this were just a big
play, and it can be very frustrating to feel unable to express
important aspects of who we are, especially when we feel even more so
in mundane life.  This is true for pagans, homosexuals, and other
minorities, as Li Kung Lo has so graciously pointed out.  The
courtesy and tolerance in the SCA has quite a strong appeal, and
rightly so, I think, and it takes a certain willingness to flaunt
expectations to enjoy the Society in the first place.

To take a humorous example, when I went to the March for Women's Lives
in Washington DC this weekend, I half expected to see a group of
people in garb with a banner saying "Barbarians for Choice" or
something :-).  I didn't, but it wouldn't have surprised me... 

It is very frustrating to find places where this courtesy and
tolerance seem to disappear.

Sometimes it can be very hard to strike a balance between being
yourself and something that can best be summed up by "not spoiling
other people's fun." Now, things like playing the Conan soundtrack at
5:30 AM at Pennsic (to help prepare your fighters, I suppose...sigh)
is pretty clearly overstepping the bounds.  On the other hand, with
things that are not so universally accepted, such as sexual
orientation and so on, it's harder to figure out.  Personally, I tend
towards the view that the King and Queen are in part symbols of the
Crown and kingdom, and that part of the ancient symbolism we employ is
the idea that the King and Queen form complementary parts of a whole,
and that having one male and one female is a reasonable (not to
mention traditional) way to show that.  I think a same-sex royal
couple could be fun, but even I don't think it would feel quite right,
if only because there isn't even a wisp of a period framework.
However, I think there's definitely a great possibility for schtick
(another important part of the Society, when done right...) with a
King and King's Champion who were openly attached, or a Queen and
Queen's Champion (or head lady-in-waiting, or whatever).  This has in
fact been done many times with opposite-sex couples where only one of
them was royalty at the time, and it seems to work pretty well. 

Ah well, back to work.

Peace,

Amanda
(still working on a documentable SCA surname...)
