In article <8904101416.AA22177@tut.cis.ohio-state.edu> LEE_JES%CTSTATEU.BITNET@MITVMA.MIT.EDU (Jeffrey S. Lee) writes:

>    I have been told that persona names can be bounced if they are too similar
> to already-registered names.  If this is so, then can someone utilise
> variations on their registered name for secondary/tertiary personae?  (For
> instance, if I wished to use "Geoffrey de Shipbrook" as a variation
> of my name, would it be acceptable?)
>    Also, can a secondary persona use the same device as the primary persona?

Good my lord Godfrey,

You touch some interesting points here.  Basically, the College of
Arms has always tried to avoid making any rules about secondary
personae, or, indeed, about any persona.  For the most part, the
College assumes that it always is dealing with the primary persona.  A
individual may register one alternate persona name if it is submitted
with a badge for that persona, and that alternate name is judged by
the same criteria as any other name.  However, the College does not
regulate persona, or how you use your persona, or anything like that.

As it happens, the specific example you choose is moot: Since Godfrey
& Geoffrey were often used interchangably in period, the two names
Godfrey de Shipbrook and Geoffrey de Shipbrook would almost certainly
refer to the same person.  Therefore, you can confidently use either
one any way you want.  Your device is yours.  You can use it any way
you want to.

That's the official opinion.


Now my own opinions:

I find the whole idea of "official" alternate persona to be remarkably
confusing.  I can understand wanting to show up, say, Japanese, from
time to time, or wanting to create and adopt a special persona for a
particular event, but I see no reason to formalize such things.  It
just confuses people.  The fantasy of the SCA allows you to be from
any medieval culture you like, at any time.  You can wear any clothes
you want.  BUT...changing your name every other week simply makes
everyone forget who you are.

Registered names can be thought of as "official" personae.  This is
the name under which you would be called into court, or compact an
apprenticeship.  "Unofficial" personae and alternate names are just
for fun, and should generally not be taken beyond that status.

Good cheer.

	Arval.
