Re: Same Sex Consorts
 
Such a view is probably the more unpopular, but I do support
opposite sex consorts.  The SCA is always in (productive)
tension over the Middle Ages as they were, and the Middle
Ages as they should have been.  Too much of either can make
life very unpleasant.
 
Like William, I would not have a problem with a monarch
who was gay in his/her private life. I would have a problem
with someone who used the throne as a podium for nearly any
personal belief or prejudice, and that includes Christianity,
although mundanely I am a Christian.  (Enid thinks she is
Christian, but does lots of stuff the inquisition will frown
on 700 years later).
 
I would draw my particular line for authenticity on the
monarchy.  There should be a male and a female monarch.
Otherwise we are playing some other game (ancient Sparta?).
 
Again, either monarch can be gay in his/her private life.
This is true even if some groups consider homosexuality as a sin.
If we bar what one group considers sinners, we wind up barring
adulterers, people who have had abortions,  people who
have no religious beliefs, and on and on.   I can't support
that, and it sounds like no-one else on the Rialto would
either.  I would, however,  draw
the line at having a cannibal or pederast on the throne, however,
because they harm people who have no choice or defense against
them.  (And that argument is all in John Stuart Mills.)
 
Re: The Character of the Monarch and Fealty
 
