In article <8904072237.AA16422@tut.cis.ohio-state.edu>, crf@GNV.IFAS.UFL.EDU
 ("FEINSTEIN, CHERYL") says:
>Consider:  your group is known as a Duchy because some Duke lives there.
>Fine.  What happens if the Duke moves?  Does the title return to that of
>Barony?  What about the Baron?  What about the Registry, and your Kingdom
>Chronicler, trying to keep track of all this?
>                                    Cher de Bellevue

     Why shouldn't it just remain a Duchy?  Because the Duke/Duchess
doesn't live there, or because she/he/it might no longer be a "citizen"
of that Kingdom?  That's hardly a period attitude!  In period, there was
(at least in many parts of the world) no such thing as citizenship, and
it was perfectly okay to be the subject of two different Kings.  In fact,
if I'm not totally confused, the Kings of England used to do homage to
the Kings of France, because the Kings of England were also the Dukes of
Normandy.  And later on, the situation often arose that one person was
King of several different Kingdoms at once.  What mattered was not where
you were born, or where you lived, but who your parents were.
     This all changed as feudalism was replaced by capitalism, and as
wealthy merchants came to be as powerful as hereditary nobles.  Our ideas
of "citizenship," and to some extent of nationalism, reflect an urban,
bourgeois (sp???) point of view.  As any Medieval aristocrat knew, the
things that really matter are fealty and homage.
     So - what does this imply in the context of the SCA?  First, most of
us should see ourselves not as citizens of a Kingdom, but as subjects of
a King (or in some cases, of two or more Kings).  We should not worry
about such trivial matters as which kingdom we're living in.  Perhaps we
should even be allowed to hold office in more than one Kingdom, though if
an officer is going to be in a distant Kingdom for too long a time, they
should leave a deputy to take over their duties in their absence.  And,
of course, we should have nobles who have titles, and "land," in two or
more different Kingdoms.  After all, it's period. ;-)

Henry of Maldon (Alex Clark), Shire of Nithgaard in the East Kingdom
(State College / Bellefonte, Pa.)

