Date: Sun, 9 Apr 89 10:12 ADT
From: JENNIFER BANKIER <BANKIER%AC.DAL.CA@mitvma.mit.edu>
Subject: Fertility as a basis for monarchy

I am slightly stunned by Paul Tien-Shih Lee's argument that
eligibility for monarchy in the SCA (in the context of the
discussion of same sex consorts) should be based on a historical
requirement that monarchs in our period be willing to serve
as "propagator of the Realm".  This argument is flawed
on a wide range of bases.

First it assumes that gay people don't propagate themselves.
I wonder why the large number of gay people that I know with
kids got them?  Some of them had heterox

kids got them?  Some of them had heterosexual marriages
(as I suspect did a lot of medieval gay people).
It is also possible to induce pregnancy outside marriage
by occasional acts of sex.  In the modern era there is
artificial insemination, and some of the techniques in
this area would probably have worked in the middle ages
too (e.g turkey basters or their medieval equivalent).

Second, in the SCA we definitely *don't* propagate
the royal line by heridity.  If propagation is the
key variable for royalty, then we'd better change
our means of selecting monarchs pretty quickly if
authenticity is always to be the governing characteristic.
(Presumably, we picked combat tourneys as the means
of selection because it offended modern senses of fairness
and equality of opportunity for one person to be ruling
monarch in the SCA for their full life, and pass it on
to their eldest son.)

(Note also the periodic suggestions that we should
change the means of monarchical selection to let someone
other than stellar sword-fighters be ruling sovereign,
e.g. the artisans: that isn't period either, but the
issue won't be settled by period considerations.)

If propagation/fertility is to be the governing characteristic,
then we'd better adopt a lot of other new rules too.
No person who happens to be infertile should be eligible
to be monarch ... whether this is due to age, medical operation,
birth characteristics, disease that affects fertility
(e.g. hysterectomy or pelvic inflammatory disease in females)
or who has an infertile consort.  [I happen to be infertile,
by the way.]  This would be quite authentic, since nasty
things sometimes happened to monarchs without kids, especially
female consorts, but occasionally to male Kings too.
I suspect modern sensibilities would be severely offended by
this rule, however, if its target were someone other than
gay people.

I repeat that the SCA is inauthentic in an enormous range
of its practices as a reflection of the modern needs,
experiences, and values of its members.  We have never
insisted on authentic roles or personnas for black members
for example, or restricted the options of Jewish people
within the society, despite the fact that the Jews suffered
seriously from anti-semitism in our era, and there weren't
any black English Dukes, Counts or whatever.

If the oppression of gay people were as offensive to the
majority of members of the SCA as the oppression of
black people, jewish people, or female people, I'm sure
the rules we are discussing would be rapidly changed.
(There are religious values that justify the oppression
of women, jews, and black people in some religions too,
but this hasn't governed the rules adopted by the society
as a whole.)   Unfortunately, SCA consciousness is
not as tolerant to gay people at pr esent as it is to
these other groups.

JKB

