In recent postings people have been making a fundamental error:  They are
confusing their personas with themselves.  Personas are fictional characters,
not real people.  We are actors in a vast unscripted fantasy.  It is important
to remember that our personas would do many things that we would not.  Awilda
Halfdane is an Odin-worshipping Viking who would be quite willing to sacrifice
prisoners taken in battle to Odin.  Gwen Johnson does not even fight, and is
known for rescuing kittens.  This is true of many people--Baron Northwoods
hanged John Hobbit for starting the Squires' Revolt many years ago.
Needlesstosay, no murder was done, it was only acting.  And when we swear
fealty, or bow to monarchs, we are still only acting.  Therefore the personal
preferences of royalty don't matter, nor does the fact that the king is a real
stinker.   I respect all kings, even though I do not necessarily respect the
man who is playing king. 

It is very rare that someone's personal affairs  intrude on the fantasy in such
a way that the rest of our personas must notice.  Mind you, we the real people
notice a lot more than our personas do.  I notice that I arrive at Pennsic War
in an automobile, Awilda is convinced that she arrived by longship.  And I know
that my tent is made of nylon, Awilda knows that her tent is made of canvas.
And when King Michael the Ineffable of the Midrealm stole the royal regalia,
all the personas who were subjects of the Midrealm noticed that too.  But it
was the mundane persons who sued.  The medeival personas vowed vengeance and
dismemberment if they ever laid hands on him.  Fortunately, such incidents are
rare.

So, when we debate about the restrictions, we must remember the differences
between ourselves and our personas.  If a person is playing a Jewish persona,
regardless of whether their mundane religion allows them to swear fealty or
not, they cannot do so without violating their persona.  And if a person is
Jewish, that does not necessarily mean that his persona is.  I have known
Gentiles to play Jews, and I have known Jews to play Gentiles.  I even played a
Christian for a while, but I found I offended fewer people by being a pagan.
The difficulty was due to the fact that people assumed persona  and person were
the same.  They are not. 

So we have confused cases.  William de Corbie says he would not swear fealty to
an openly gay king.  I presume he means the openly gay persona of a king. It
is quite  possible for someone to be openly gay, but not to have an openly gay
persona.  Confusing, yes, but perfectly reasonable. We already have the really
confusing situation of SCA marriages, SCA relationships, and SCA religions. Why
not SCA sexual preferences?

Yours in service,
