Date:     Sun, 9 Apr 89 13:55 EST
From:     <CRF%IFASGNV.BITNET@mitvma.mit.edu>
Subject:  Homosexuality and discrimination

Greetings!

Firstly, a simple statement of fact:  for everyone's information, the reason
all official documents of the SCA, Inc. (_Corpora_ and Kingdom Laws) use non
gender-specific language is that mundane civil rights laws mandate it.
Gender-specific language could be used in a discriminatory manner, as a
discriminatory filter.

Ditto, women fighting.  Apart from the hard documentation that women fighters
*did* exist in period, denying women from participating in the martial arts
aspects of the Society is mundanely illegal, period.

Now:  let us face one unpleasant fact.  Discrimination against individuals on
the basis of sexual preference is, by and large, perfectly legal.  There are
places where ordinances exist to protect homosexuals from discrimination, but
these are the exception, not the rule.  I had one mundane friend who was
evicted from the apartment he had lived in for 13 years because the landlord
discovered he was gay.  The landlord was perfectly within his legal rights,
and my friend had no recourse whatsoever.

So, like it or not, homophobia remains as the one socially-acceptable, legal
form of discrimination.

This being the case, I reiterate my support of the policy of requiring the
Sovereign and Consort to be of opposing genders (please see my previous
remarks on this subject for further explanation).  **This is NOT to say I
_like_ it!**  Quite the contrary!  But, I *do* view it as a "necessary evil".

And, weak as "it isn't period" is, it's also true.

So, I don't think those clauses in _Corpora_ will change until mundane law
changes, and mandates such.  Frankly, until that time, I think we're safer
that way.

In response to William de Corbie:  I do not regard this discussion to be about
allowing the sexual preferences of a would-be Crown to intrude upon official
life, as it is about freedom to choose one's consort regardless of *anything*
other than suitability as a working partner.  The issues of homosexuality,
homophobia, etc., are relevant corollaries.

On a related point:  take it from me, when you're interested in the kinds
of things us Society-types are interested in (brewing, armors, steel toys,
costuming, history, etc.) you can be as much a misfit in the gay community as
anywhere else.  The SCA is, even now, the place I feel most accepted and most
at home.


