[lots 'o SCA stuff which I'm in the dark about, but general sense of OK-ness
with Kings and Queens with same sex consorts, deleted]

I'm not very familiar with the SCA as it currently operates but I would
like to take a stab at this issues from a slightly diffent perspective.

It seems to me that the SCA must operate from the basis of historical
possiblity, but necessarily historical accuracy.  In fact, at least one
previous posting says as much.  If this is true, it would mean that the
domain of your activities cannot surpass certain historical, as well as
cultural boundries.  In the simplest cases, it would mean that knights
don't carry guns.  From there, you can have more and more elaborate rules
as the restrictions becomes more and more "artificial", e.g. some rule
which forbids contact between royalty and commoners.  Historically
reasonable, but silly by modern standards.

At first, the idea of Kings and Queens having opposite sex consorts does
seem to be an artifice rooted in antiquity.  However, closer examination
reveals that certain modern assumptions cannot be applied to historical or
near-historical situations.  Namely that the King/Queen and consort are
only political leaders and that these heads of state were chosen by the
Gentle Persons of a Realm from some pool of such Personages once every
several Anno.  What our modern preception fail to grasp is that the
King/Queen pair also perform the functions of social, economical, as well as
biological leaders.

The structure of any given "Realm" which has a King/Quenn type pair at the
top can almost always be distilled downed to some variation of a clan or an
extended family.  One of the most important aspects of this type of
organization is the establishment of loyalty.  Loyalty is given to the head
of the clan and the (usually) descendents, that is to say, loyalty is to
the "blood" of the leader.

If you are to assume that "blood" doesn't matter, you are then basing the
tenents of your role-playing on something other than a historically *sound*
model.  Note that accuracy is not the issue here.  It is enough to assume
certain broad, historical trends which serve as backdrops to your own
version of the past.  But the same trends which prevent Huns from using
tactical nuclear devices on the Franks (do you go back that far?) also
prevent you from simulating societies which allowed for and supported
leaders who did not consort with their opposite sex, for the simple reason
that there would be no offspring to carry on the "blood".

If you are dubious about the social impact of "normal" royalty, just look
at the English.  They are a parliamentarian democracy with the Queen as
titular head of state, who has very little real power.  And yet, I'll bet
you that if tomorrow, all sentiments of homophobia were to erase theselves
from English society, the people would still be in an uproar if both
Charles and Andrew came out of the closet and then proved that they did not
sire their children.  The issue here is the *perceived* role of a King or a
Queen as the propagator of the Realm.  If the King or Queen is unable or
unwilling because of their sexual preference to propagate their issue, the
people of the Realm cannot have great hopes for the Realm's propagation
either.

My personnal feeelings on this matter is that I could not support a monarch
who is not willing to propagate the line.  Setting this in a more
historical context, we can imagine a case where we have a monarch who
chooses a same sex consort, and my personal feelings are shared by most or
the members of Peerage.  This doesn't even have to do with homosexuality; the
same is true if the monarch is sterile.  (This is just like not betting on
a knight with no arms to win a joust.  Physical disablity is just an
explanation, there's still no percentage in it.)  The perception here is
that practicing heterosexal/child creating activities are important
qualifications in a monarch.  Without imposing some sort of extremely
elaborate and artifical external structure (see Samual R. Delaney's
Neverion stories), practicing of exclusively homosexal behavior at a public
level does not work when the people involved are Kings and Queens.

That's my two bits worth.  I would gladly welcome any further discussion on
this.  I'd really like to see how the people in this newgroup feel about
some of my generalizations.


