Subject: mead making

The best source for mead recipes is 

The closet of the eminently learned sir Kenelm Digbie Kt opened:
whereby is discovered several ways for making of metheglin, Sider, Cherry-Wine,
&c.  together with excellent directions for cookery: 
as also for preserving, conserving, candying, &c.
(1669)

The book has been reprinted in fascimile form as volume VI of the
Mallinckrodt Collection Food Classics.  A photocopy reprint was done in
Carolingia many years ago, and may still be available.

Kenelm's recipes vary widely in strength from 18 parts water to one part honey
(in "hydromel as I made it weak for the Queen Mother") up to 2 1/2 parts
water to one part honey.  Most of his recipe use a ratio between 3 and 6 to
one.  His yeast source is either ale barm or toast (depending on the recipe).


My best mead was made with 5 lbs of honey to each gallon of water (about 2 to 
1), which made a sweet dessert wine, comparable to a good sherry.
(This mead won the brewing contest at Ice Dragon in 1984.)
Here is a short form of the recipe:
3 gallons water
16 lbs honey (Calif wildflower)
1/4 cup keemun tea
1/4 cup oolong tea
2 tsp cinnamon
1/2 tsp whole anise seed
1 tsp crushed cardamom
20 whole allspice (crushed)
2 1/4 tsp crushed galingale root

Boil the water with the tea and spices, add the honey but do not boil it.
When cooled to 100 degrees F, add wine yeast. (I start the wine yeast in
a cup of water with a little honey added.)

Ferment for about 2 weeks (I ferment in the stainless steel pot that I boil
the water in), then siphon into a glass bottle with a fermentation
lock, leaving the sediment (tea leaves and dead yeast) behind.
Three weeks to a month later, siphon into another bottle.
Three months later siphon again.
Three months later siphon into final 750ml bottles, and store in a
cool place for a year or two.

I do not use sulphites for sterilization, but boil everything.
To sterilize a 5 gallon bottle, I fill it with boiling water and
let it stand for 15 minutes.
I've never had a batch turn to vinegar.

Some hints:
1) cleaniness is everything--sterilize anything that touches the mead.
2) the weaker the mead, the sooner it is ready.
3) use ale or beer yeasts for weak meads, white wine yeast for strong ones.
4) Adding tea for tanin is not a period practice, but helps give
character to strong meads.
5) If you don't want to wait months for the mead to clarify before bottling,
try boiling the honey with the water.  Many of Digby's recipes call
for it, and it does help coagulate the pollen proteins so they
precipitate out faster.  I think there is some loss of flavor, but if
you use commercial honey, it has already been cooked anyway.
6) Bottle in strong bottles, particularly if the mead is not quite
clear when you bottle it.  Don't wire corks onto champagne bottles
(there's less mess from poppoing corks than from exploding bottles).
7)Ferment warm and age cool. 


If you are making an ale-strength mead (say 2lbs of honey to a gallon
of water), allow 3-6 months.  If you're making a wine mead, allow 1-5 years.
If you try to hurry, you'll end up with a yeast infusion that tastes like
uncooked bread dough.

I have a more detailed recipe on making mead on mag tape.
If there is interest, I could retrieve it.  Unfortunately, it is in
TeX format, so may be difficult for people to read.

