If I read with some cynicism the rationalizations that same-sex
royal couples should not be allowed in the SCA because "It isn't
period", it's because I'm a survivor of the "Women shouldn't be
allowed to fight because it isn't period" battles.  (My, that
dates me.)

Although those of us who wanted to fight tried to combat this
by providing period examples of women who did fight, I don't think
this is what ultimately changed the rules.

It seems likely that they were ultimately changed because this *is*
the Society for *Creative* Anachronism.  We try to replicate
constructive medieval practices, not those that were destructive
or unhealthy (e.g. smallpox, anti-semitism).\

I suspect the women-fighting rule was ultimately changed because
it offended the modern sensibilities of both female and many
male society members.

The "same sex consort" rules can be changed, and will be changed
if Society sensibilities recognize that homophobia was and is
as offensive in our own society as sexism is.

(My recollection is that at least one English King was murdered
in a particularly nasty way ... hot irons up the anus ... in
part because he was gay.  Is this a medieval value that we want
to honor?)

