Greetings!

In response to Ellen Eades' remarks regarding homophobia in the Society, and
same-sex Crowns:  firstly, there are few places as tolerant as the SCA, and I
have found none more tolerant.  I have rarely encountered homophobia in the
Society, and then only in individuals who were pretty damned uptight to begin
with (this, by the way, is coming from a New York Jew now living in the
South...).  Second:  if one stops to think about it, one can see the reasoning
behind the requirement in _Corpora_ that the Sovereign and Consort be of
different genders.  After all, there ain't no way it can be said to be period!
Moreover, it is in general safer publicity-wise, especially with some of the
recent image problems tabloid television has engendered:  like it or not,
enough people think we're wierd and suspicious as it is.  We certainly don't
need to exacerbate the situation!

Those of us who are gay, and/or feel that the prohibition of same-sex Crowns
is discriminatory, and/or that such would be harmless and a great deal of fun
besides, or whatever, may have perfectly valid points.  Unfortunately, that
doesn't make the idea of same-sex Crowns more feasible, or wiser.

With respect to Ariel of Caer Myrddin's "letter of dis-recommendation":  I
wonder, milady, if you copied your letter to the Principal or Secretary of the
polling Order in question?  You are absolutely correct in your statement that
the Crown will do as it pleases.  However, if the polling Order in question is
to make a decision on the nomination they need the same info as the Crown.  If
the Crown had this negative input and the Order didn't, mayhap they supported
the nomination.  Yes, the award is bestowed at the Crown's pleasure.   And
yes, the Crown is free to bestow the award over the Order's objections.  But
most Crowns, when faced with a negative poll (especially by a large margin),
will decline to do so:  it creates too many undesirable repercussions.


