Oh, well. Here we have another of those things where medieval theory and
practice conflict with modern ideology. In our modern ideology, tolerance 
is paramount and anyone who does not accept openly practiced homosexuality
is considered a "dinosaur brain" or something in that order - a bigot, a
backward conservative asshole of the First Degree.

Let me tell you about my own belief. As a Christian, I cannot accept homo-
sexual relationships as "good" in a moral sense. I would like to make it
clear that I am *not* a homophobe. I have several friends who are gay, and
though we have our differences, I do not regard them as more sinful, evil
or bad than myself. The intention of this posting is *not* to start a
debate about the ethical validity of homosexual relationships.

As a Christian I believe that God speaks through the bible. I am bound by
his words. Since the bible clearly forbids homosexual acts (not homosexual
thoughts or inclinations), I am bound by this and cannot accept such acts
as being in accordance with God's will. I consider homosexual inclination
a~ part of the damage we all suffered through the fall of mankind, and I
consider homosexual acts as sin. These sins are no worse, nor any better 
than other sins (many of which I myself commit). 

Still, it is clear to me that I could not serve or swear fealty to a king
who is an active homosexual. Active homosexuality means that the person
is saying "I am gay, and I have intercourse with people of my own sex, and
I believe that it is right to do so". Regardless of wether this king had
a consort of the same sex or inclination, I would see it as a religious
duty not to serve him/her - *not* because this person is gay, but because
he/she is saying that it is right to commit homosexual acts.

My reaction would be the same if there was a king who said he was a thief
and considered it right to steal, or if he supported any other sin that
the bible condemns. Therefore, I am very glad that the current Corpora
states that the consort shall be of the opposite sex. I realize that I
may have served kings and princes who were openly gay, but as long as
I didn't know about it, it made no difference. It would be quite a different
thing if the king used his throne as a platform for "gay liberation", making
it an obvious part of his reign that he was gay. I could not serve such
a reign.

The purpose of this posting is to illuminate the point that the sexual
inclinations of the king/queen are best kept out of the official life
of the Society. Since default is a male/female king and queen, this is
what we should have.

