I merely pointed out that there was a great difference between the Inquisition
(in general) and the fanatic, hysteric witch-hunts of the 16th and 17th cen-
turies. The witch-hunts are often confused with the Inquisition, but are a
different phenomenon.

The Inquisition was not always the same. It existed and acted over several
hundreds of years in many different countries, and the examples of how it
worked which you quote may be true *about one place at one time*, but they
are not true about *all* of the medieval Inquisition in *all* places and at
all times. Read "Montaillou" by LeRoy Ladurie, for instance. It is based 
on the protocols of the Inquisition.

Ite Inquisition was a qualified court. That sets it apart from a witch-burning
mob of hysteric people. The Inquisition examined evidence. No doubt they
committed atrocities by modern standards. But the standard horror-image is
vastly exaggerated.

And it remains true that hose who were killed in the witch-hunts were not
pagans or witches, just plain women who had the misfortune of being accused.
Thus, they are not martyrs to the cause of witchcraft. 

