I don't know.  Wouldn't those among us of the Jewish persuasion consider all
Christian heretical? :-)
In any case I've been looking through my books and talking to my favorite
student of things Central American and have come up with an interesting case
of _non_-survival of a religion, nay, most of a culture, the Mayans. Unlike
most of the indigenous European religions the Mayan body of beliefs and tradi-
tions was almost completely written.  Very little of it was passed down
orally.  When the body of Mayan literature was burned by the conquistadors
(may their names and memories be erased) the vast majority of Mayan lore
was completely lost within a generation.  Judaism may have survived by virtue
of its redundant system of knowledge preservation.  If the Talmud was burned
it could (and was) reconstructed from memory (!!).  If learned rabbis were
killed the books still survived.

It's interesting. Knowledge preserved solely in one fashion is fragile.
Knowledge preserved in several media is more likely to last. It makes one
wonder what would happen should we lose the bulk of our books.  Could any
of us pas the pin test on the CRC? The pin test was/is a way of testing
Talmudic students on their knowledge.  Take a pin. Stick it through a few
pages of a volume of Talmud.  Ask the student to reconstruct the arguments,
text, and opinions contained on those pages.

There are other examples of traditions surviving the advent of Christianity
and persecution albeit not completely unchanged.  The martial arts of
the Phillipines, Okinawa, Indonesia, and to some extent Africa (among
slaves in Brazil.  I don't know anything about their survival in Africa)
continued on through centuries of suppression.  A consistently successful
tactic was to call it colorful native dancing, perfectly harmless....
The Spanish in the Phillipines and the Portugese in Brazil even encouraged
the practice.  The simple peasants danced so beautifully and seemed so
_happy_ while they were dancing.  Kepts them out of trouble.  Yup.
Does anyone know of other traditions, particularly in Europe, which survived
the Middle Ages and the Church by similar camaflogue?
