I've been a good girl and dropped the religion subject because it's been worn
thin, but William, you got my goat with the insistance that the Inquisition was
a qualified court of law operating under the same procedures as other courts of
the time.  the Inquisition was NOT--and the jurists of the time knew it, but
excused the excesses and illegaliites of the Inquisition as a necessary evil in
order to combat the terrible horrible spector of witch craft.  I am going to
quote some originals sources as they Appear in the Encyclopedia of Witchcraft
and Demonology by Rossell Hope Robbins, published first in 1959, published most
recently by Bonanza Books of New York.  The introduction describes itself as "a
distillation of more than a thousand primary works on withcraft".   The
Encyclopedia is *the* standard reference on witchcraft.  

"A distinguished professor of law at the University of Toulouse advocates the
suspension of rules in witch trials because 'not one out of a million witches
would be accused or punished, if regular legal procedure were followed.'"
[This was in 1580, the author was Jean Bodin-Awilda]

"Trials for wichcraft were not designed to establish guilt or innocence. but to
condemn the accused as ssoon as possible."

"Any person having a mole, wen, scar or bunion is considered to possess a
devil's mark and is therefore to be executed as a witch.  A celebrated professor
of law at Cologne said that no one with such a mark could have lived a
blameless life.

"Every witch had her familiars...While imprisoned, her cell is to be watched
carefully for spiders and flies; any insect not caught is presumed to have
escaped because of its diabolical powers, thus proving the accused guilty.

"'Switzerland has been compelled to wipe out many of her villages on their
account.  Travelers in the Lorraine may see thousands of the stakes to which
witches are bound.'"

"Witchcraft was remorselessly attacked by both civil and church authorities; it
resulted in tens of thousands of people being legally murdered."

"For a century, the Inquisition attacked Waldenses and Cathari and other
heretical sects in southern France; it worked so successfully that it killed
most of the heretics and so dried up the sources of its funds.  In 1375 the
Inquisitor Eymeric lamented;"IN our days, there are no more rich heretics, so
that princes, not seeing much money in the prospect, will not  put themselves
to any expense; it is a pity that so salutory an institution as ours should be
so uncertain of its future."

[Please note that Robbins figure of "tens of thousands" is ONLY the number of
people slain for the  specific charge of witchcraft.  Many other kinds of heretics
were also burned, making a much larger total death toll.-Awilda]

"One typical set of standardized questions was used at Colmar, in Lorraine
over the three centuries of the mania:
1. How long have you been a witch?
2. Why did ypu become a witch?
22. Who are your accomplices in evil?
26. What tempests have you raised, and who helped you to produce them?"

[The total standard questions number over a hundred and are all of the "Have
you stopped beating your wife?" kind-Awilda]

"When it is remembered that the accused had to answer, that refusal was deemed
tacitunity necessitating harsher torture, that judges or torturers would prompt
the accused's memory, the uniformity of confessions is no mystery."

[The Inquisition had a standard set of questions that were so well known that
they were referred by number in the trial transcripts.  Individual cases were
rarely examined on their own merits. If a person was accused, they were
tortured until they confessed-the longest anyone ever resisted torture was
about three weeks.  In England where torture was prohibited they used sleep
deprivation, starvation, thirst, and exhaustion to obtain confessions.  Those
who confessed were strangled before being burned, those who recanted their
confessions--and many did--were burned to death.-Awilda]

"Other aspects of inquisitorial laws are just as intolerable:

1. The procedure was kept secret.

2. Common report was accepted as an indication of guilt.  In theory this
consisted of the testimony of several trustworthy persons; in practice, hearsay
gossip or denunciations given under torture.  The accused had to disprove the
rumours.

3.Frequently, precise charges were concealed from the accused.  Very
occassionally, he was allowed a lawyer appointed by the court, but the lawyer
had to take care lest he defend the accused too well and so himself be accused
of befriending a heretic.  Finally, even this pretense was a bolished.

4.Witnesses or informers were kept secret...

5.Persons normally barred from giving evidence in all other trials were
permitted and encouraged to testify in witch trials-children of ten years and
younger, perjurers and felons, and excommunicates.

6.No favorable evidence about the accused's previous life and character...

7. A witness for the accused was presumed to be a friend, and therefore guilty
by a association of the same crime.

8. Torture was always employed, nor was there any limit to its severity or
duration.  If the accused died under torture, it was said that the devil broke
his neck. Even if the accused confessed without torture,  nevertheless he had
to make his confession under torture; it was assumed that he might have
confessed falsely just to avoid torture.  After torture, the accused had to
repeat his confession "freely" and the court record would so state.

9. The most severe torture was reserved to make the accused an informer; often
names of "accomplices: were suggested to him by the judges or hangmen.

10. No one accused was ever found innocent.  At best his case would be declared
Not Proven, and the trial could be reopened at any time.  However, this was
theoretical, for in practice the accused was tortured until he confessed or
died under the torture."

"It took two hundred years to burn, at a conservative estimate, 200,000 witches....What
makes witchcraft so repellant, and morally lower than fascism, is that
throughout civilized Europe, in every country with the possible later exception
