Subject: On boat wars and grand entrances

I enjoyed Robayyan Tour d'Elandris's description of the Boat Wars.  Two teams
of fighters did a longboat battle at Pennsic XIII, and it was a lot of fun to
watch.  (Some of my best Pennsic pictures are from that battle.)

In response to William de Corbie's account of announcing the grand entrance
of nobles in the movies: Does anybody remember the scene in Monty Python's 
"Jabberwocky" where the warden has to announce all the King's titles before 
anyone can sit down at Court?

I would assume (but will have to hit the books to come up with facts, if there
are any) that people would be announced depending on rank, and probably also
depending on how big the banquet was.  For instance, the feast at a royal
wedding would probably have more nobles present who needed to be announced
than would a banquet at a baronial hunting manor.  Did they go to the trouble
of announcing each and every one?  They may well have.  The more important the
person, the more likely a long string of titles would be attached during the
announcement.  (We moderns may not make such a big deal of this, but back then
it would have: If you had just conquered or inherited a new territory, it 
would mean something to be called "Lord of XXXX" along with everything else,
and in front of the crowd assembled.)

As for the staff-banging: We might not find any documentation for this, but I
know from experience that a herald with a staff can usually command more
attention than one without... especially after having made a few dozen
announcements.

One of the households I belong to has a custom of announcing the arrival of
guests to their camp at Pennsic, but this is the only place I see such a thing
in the SCA.  It's probably just as well, too; otherwise, East Kingdom Twelfth
Night would take 2 1/2 weeks and give laryngitis to 25 heralds.

On bowing when a lady enters the room:  I'm only guessing here, but I'll try
to check a real source (if one exists): it is possible that such a thing might
also have occurred in period, if the lady were either of high rank or were the
lady of the house.  The only precedent I can think of would be the "laws of
courtesy" that accompanied the code of courtly love.  The original premise of
the code was that men should revere all ladies as they did the Holy Virgin (of
course, this acquired more earthy connotations in practice).

I'll try to find some good sources on these customs; I suspect that period
literature might be the only place where details like this would be mentioned.
If anyone has any suggestions on where to look, please post; William's questions
have made me curious.

Many thanks...

