PLEASE FORGIVE ME IF THIS POSTING APPEARS TWICE.  I'M STILL TRYING TO FIGURE
OUT WHAT RECENT UPGRADES TO OUR MAIL SYSTEM WILL AND WON'T DO!


Greetings!

Well, Fool's War was a *HUGE* blast-- if the Shire of Novus Matisco is trying
to create "Pennsic South" they're on the way!  The tri-Kingdom war was won by
Meridies, with Trimaris second, and Atlantia third.  Trimaris fielded the most
fighters, so Meridies and Atlantia double-teamed us in the Beach and Woods
Battles.  Atlantia won the former battle, Meridies the latter.  Meridies won
the three-way Bridge Battle after much time spent by all three armies thumbing
their noses at each other from behind their shield walls.

The Arts/Sci competition was 1/3 of the points this year.  Trimaris sewed it
up, placing first in 18 out of 28 categories (8 of those were from *my
Barony*, y'all!), let alone the second's and third's-- which explains how we
came in ahead of Atlantia in the war, overall.

Now, on to more serious things...

LANDED TITLES:  Whereas I will gladly admit that the idea of Counties, Duchys,
etc., is neato-spiffy-keen, I could never support its implementation; it's
simply not practical from the standpoint of Corporate administration.  Let
alone the spectre of (shudder!) more bureaucracy.

Consider:  your group is known as a Duchy because some Duke lives there.
Fine.  What happens if the Duke moves?  Does the title return to that of
Barony?  What about the Baron?  What about the Registry, and your Kingdom
Chronicler, trying to keep track of all this?

Realistically, what we've got is the most practical set-up as far as groups'
status goes.  It also reflects what was probably the most common rank of
nobility, apart from knight.

What is to me far more cogent is the matter of rank and resulting precedence.
I agree with Awilda Halfdane about the titles with the highest precedence
going to those who serve, however hard they work, for extremely short,
well-defined periods of time.  I do *not* think they shouldn't get the titles;
it's not that some former King doesn't deserve the rank of Count.  I just
think that the Peers and Landed Nobility should have higher precedence,
because theirs is a contribution on a long-term scale.  So, I just wish there
was some practical way to change the Order of Precedence. But, I am fully
aware that to do so at this late date would be to result in something totally
unrelated to period practice and reality.

Btw-- I also wish there were a practical way for non-stick types to compete
for the Crown.

HANDICAPPED/CHIURGEON:  Both Awilda Halfdane and Li Kung Lo have addressed
this subject most eloquently.  I think they have each said things we *all*
need to pay attention to.  To their words, I would only add:  those
handicapped members I have encountered strive mightily to participate and
contribute as independently as possible.  I think it behooves us all to be
aware of their efforts, and to do what we can to smooth the way for them
without infringing on their hard-won independence.  Which I freely admit can
be touchy.

As an example:  here in Trimaris we have a young lady who is a very talented
artist, and who works with the heralds on scrolls.  She is confined to a
wheelchair.  Now, Trimaris is a *very* sandy place.  So, whenever I see this
lady rolling off to some part of a site, I ask if she thinks she's going to
need help getting across some soft sand.  No more; no less.  Usually, she's
thought of a route consisting entirely of firm terra :-).  Occassionally,
however, she does get bogged down and need assistance-- and she can usually
anticipate the situation.  This being the case, she isn't insulted by the
question; rather she appreciates that someone else has perceived the potential
problem.

YEASTS:  I have found that using ale yeasts to brew meads tends to result in
over-carbonation (can you say **BOOM!!**?).  Far better results (and in the
case of some of the more delicately flavored honeys, better flavor) can be
obtained using chablis yeasts.  I generally use "Montrechet," which is readily
availably at homebrew supply stores, or by mail.

PHARISEES/SADDUCEES:  Dani of the 7 Wells made some excellent points.  There
are many other factors which pertain to this particular situation in history,
such as it being the period of Jewish history wherein the priesthood was
declining, and the rabbinate growing and spreading.

All in all, I think it's best to realize that studying this period of Judaeo-
Christian history can be one's life-work; it's *that* complex.  It's also
fascinating, and the events of this era did much to shape both Judaism and
Christianity as we know them today (not to mention Islam...).

AWARDS/BEHAVIOR:  I'm very glad that Enid Aurelia elaborated on her situation
further.  Not only does it jive with what many of us have been saying, it
allows me to make one other point:  if this guy is cognizant of the
problem(s), acknowledges them, and *chooses* not to change, then:  you have
done all you can; and *he* must now live with the consequences of his choice,
freely made.  If he doesn't like the consequences, that's unfortunate; but it
was, after all, *his* decision.  And, he is perfectly free to reverse it.

When a group is dealing with someone of this ilk (who refuses to change),
oft-times only 2 courses of action remain in the end:  total ostracism; and/or
the verbal equivalent of a boot to the head!  Enid seems to have tried the
latter; it would appear that the only other course left to try is the
unpleasant one of ostracism.  Frankly, if enough people refuse to talk to,
deal with, associate with, work with, or in any way acknowledge the presence
of, this individual, he will either change or go away.  While change is of
course preferable and to be hoped for, I can't help feeling that the loss of
someone who so upsets people is no loss at all, no matter *how* much work
they've done.

I know I feel just that way about one individual who recently disappeared
after many years of much work and more problems.  The hassles just weren't
worth the work, quite frankly.

I fully realize that what I am suggesting is not at all nice, is at best
difficult, and may not even be feasible.  But it may be the only recourse
left.

Thank you, one and all, for your patience with such a long posting!


