Unto Dame Enid Aurelia and all good fisherfolk, Greetings!

About the Purple Fret scenario: We had a similar thing happen in my shire a
while ago.  The person in question was harassing ladies both within and without
our shire in the name of "friendliness", and the ladies became quite sick of it.
This man had not, however, done as much for the shire as everyone thought he 
had, but  we're all in far-off Maine and nobody's near enough to find out what
the truth is.  It was alleged that he cheated on his archery scores, too, but
no one has been able to prove that conclusively.

One thing this person did do was make many friends in "high" places.  Word came
to us that he had been placed on the equivalent poll to the Purple Fret here,
and that the rest of us were being asked our opinions on this person.

The deputy seneschal and I (I was the shire herald then) sat down and wrote a
letter to the Crown, explaining what was going on in our shire.  You might call
it a letter of dis-recommendation.  We weren't trying to be spiteful or to
keep him from getting what was his due; we just wanted to inform the Crown of
what they were dealing with.  We felt that we should, as shire officers, make 
clear what was the shire's and what was his.

In short, I feel the effort was futile.  The Crown will do as it pleases, and
it may please the Crown to bestow the award anyway.  It did in this case, and
I felt that we had never been heard.  I do regret ever sending the letter
since it obviously wasn't even taken into consideration.  Letters of dis-
recommendation are pointless, and will get you nowhere, no matter how true or
how disturbing the content may be.  If in doubt, don't do it; it won't help.

Crowns may come and Crowns may go, but polling orders will go on forever.
