Unto Lady Awilda and all others who read these words, greetings!

My lady, your thoughts about the system of nobility in the SCA are
good ones, and I would that we could put some of them into practice,
but I think it unlikely.  Revising the system of nobility as radically
as you suggest is impractical.  However, you make some good points.

The idea that Baronial tenure should be limited is an interesting one.
Indeed, in Atenveldt, that is the case: Landed Baroncy there is an
office, appointed by the Crown, with a two-year warrant.  I personally
do not like their scheme, but you have pointed out some of its
advantages.  Unfortunately, I believe it opens the door to abuses as
well.  However, I do find you idea that there should be some on-going
requirements for Baronial rank.  In practice, of course, there are: If
a Baron or Baroness is inactive, or acts in a way disapproved by her
people, then they may petition the Crown to remove her from office,
and to appoint a new Baron.  This does not happen too often, but the
system for complaint and redress is in place.  Any Kingdom, or even
any Barony, could institute requirements on their barons, or schedule
regular turn-over.  Such systems could model other forms of medieval
local government: Mayors of cities, Coucils of Aldermen, and so on.
After all, not every medieval city was ruled by a nobleman.

My notion of Landed Counts is essentially the same, except on a large
scale.  

