Date: Tue, 4 Apr 89 18:53 EDT
From: "DENNIS R. SHERMAN//ROBYYAN TORR D'ELANDRIS" <DRS%UNCVX1.BITNET@mitvma.mit.edu>
Subject: Boat War Melees

    I went to an event this past weekend that used a scenario I haven't
encountered before for fighting, and I though I'd pass it along to the folk of
the Rialto to comment on and pass on to their friends.  The event was called
Boat Wars, and the concept was Vikings vs. Celts.  Nothing new so far - we've
done this before.  What made this one different was the ship-to-ship combat,
which was arranged in such a way that I consider it safe.
    Each side had boats.  The Vikings had two longboats, while the Celts had 3
coracles (we had about 24 people fighting, more or less evenly split).  The
boats were a simple 2 dimensional 2x4 frame - 4'x8' for the longboats, 4'x4'
for the coracles.
    The boats were moved by picking them up and carrying the frame.  Anyone
could pick up and move the boats, (i.e. be crew) but each boat had to have
someone on board that was "knowledgeable about boats", called a sailor.
Actually, the longboats required two sailors, since they were so large.  Any
boat without it's requisite crew of sailors was stuck in place.
    Sailors were designated people that were fighting without shields.  One of
the modifications we'll make if we do this again is designate sailors as
people fighting single sword (one broadsword, not bastard/great sword).
Sailors were needed to enable boats to move, and sailors could also "swim".
This meant that a sailor could enter the area of the field designated as water
and go wherever they wanted, although they had to do it on their knees.
    Combat from the boats was allowed, with all melee rules as usual, with one
additional rule - just prior to engagement, there was a temporary hold while
all involved put the boat frame down on the ground, then the sides engaged.
This allowed us to have the frame out of the way where it wasn't dangerous.
We weren't going to be moving around enough for them to be much of a problem
as far as tripping was concerned.  This did mean that a sideswiping hit and
run attack from a boat wasn't possible, but it didn't seem to matter.
    The tourney field was laid out with a Viking shore at one end and a Celtic
shore at the other, with an island in the middle.  Everything else was water.
In the first scenario, a flag was placed on the island, and the island was
designated to have two beaches - the rest was rock that was impossible to land
on or climb.  Both sides started on their own shore.  Victory conditions were
defined as the side that returned the flag to their own shore first.  This was
a resurrection battle.
    The next scenario had the Celts starting on the island, this time with
only one beach, and the Vikings had to take the island.  The victor was
defined as the side that had possession of the island when the last man was
standing - no resurrection.
    The third and final scenario had both sides starting on their own shore,
and the island having two beaches.  Victory was defined as possessor of the
island in 30 minutes time.  Resurrection was allowed.
    Resurrection was handled by having the dead return to their original
shore, at which point they were immediately alive, although a sailor and a
boat were needed to return them to the island where the fighting was, since
only the sailors could swim.
    The final scenario needs a slight modification to the victory conditions -
at about 23 minutes, the Celts had possession of the island and all boats,
making it impossible for the Vikings to attack the island with their freshly
resurrected fighters.  Some sailors did attempt to swim the length of the
tourney field to steal a boat, but it was really an impossibility.
    All in all, it worked surprisingly well - I'd be happy to do it again
sometime, and I'd be interested in any other thoughts on novel ways to run
melee/tournament.

        Robyyan Torr d'Elandris                 Dennis R. Sherman
        Kapellenberg, Windmaster's Hill         Chapel Hill, NC
        Atlantia                                drs@uncvx1.bitnet


