Date: Mon,  3 Apr 89 05:15:33 EDT
From: "Pandora B. Berman" <CENT@AI.AI.MIT.EDU>
Subject: favors
Message-ID: <568625.890403.CENT@AI.AI.MIT.EDU>

Greetings to all from Lady Eowyn Eilonwy of Alewife Brook, who writes these
words in Carolingia.  I see we have found another touchy subject to discuss.

Yaakov Hamizrachi, House Nitzatzot, recently wrote:
    I have just taken up the Rattan, and would like to take my lady's
    favor into battle.  Unfortunately, neither one of us knew what one
    was, although we'd heard that this was the custom.  What exactly
    is a 'favor'?  When and how is it worn? Given? Made?

and Awilda Halfdane provided an extensive answer, which I here elaborate on
in some points:
    ...In SCA ladies usually offer favors voluntarily to men they like....
There is certainly no bar to a lord asking a lady for her favor; my
understanding is that many male fighters are simply too shy to do so.

    ...Sometimes men ask for favors -- Crown Tourney usually prompts a rash
    of favor-gifts....
Because for Crown and Coronet tourneys, each fighter is -required- to be
fighting for the honor of the gentle of the other sex with whom the fighter
intends to share his/her reign, should s/he win the tourney.  There may be
other tourneys at which each fighter is required to be wearing someone's
favor, but for the most part this courteous custom is merely encouraged.

    ...Anybody can give a favor to anybody else.  It means generally that
    you like the person.  Ladies who give out favors have usually given
    favors to several people....
Here is where we open the jar of worms.  Exactly what does a favor mean?
It means what the bearer and the giver think it means.  A favor can denote
true love, as in the case of married people or otherwise long-term couples,
or formal association, as for members of the same household, or plain
friendship.  It is perfectly reasonable for a lady to bestow her favor for
a single day of fighting, or even for a single bout, as a mark of courtesy
-- although this doesn't happen as often as it could, because ladies are
shy too.  If a lady for some reason needs her honor defended in battle, her
champion would properly wear her favor in that bout to display his
championship.  During a war between two groups, the chief lady of a group
(e.g. a Queen at Pennsic or Estrella, or a Baroness at a local-group border
war) may choose to bestow favors on all the warriors on her side.
    It is wise for the two involved to both understand what the particular
favor is intended to stand for.  If the lady thinks it's the beginning of a
beautiful friendship, and the lord merely feels improper fighting without
bearing a favor -- or the reverse -- they are going to come to grief over
this confusion.  It is entirely proper for a lady to bestow only one favor.
Those who give many usually recognize a difference between a chief favor,
which generally is worn by the lady's lord or champion, and subsidiary
favors or tokens, which are distributed to other members of her household,
friends of various degrees, or anyone else the lady chooses to so honor.

    ...Men can give favors too, but I have only ever seen it happen once.
In these parts, it is not uncommon for lords and ladies who form couples to
wear each other's favors.  This custom is particularly appropriate for
those couples in which both members fight or fence, but also pleasant
for those who merely wish to visually display their association.

As Lady Awilda noted, a favor can be anything, though the normal SCA usage
is a strip of embroidered cloth (often provided with a loop to slip the
belt through); the broidery can be anything, but is often the lady's
initial, badge, or device.  Your lady should not despair if she doesn't
embroider: one Carolingian lady for years used a plain strip of cloth
recognizable by pattern as a scrap from one of her favorite gowns; another
painted her device on one of the uppermost tiles of her lord husband's coat
of (leather) scale armor.  A favor is properly worn in any SCA event
situation, though some gentles who feel strongly about the favor-givers may
carry the favors with them always.
    In all situations it is intended to remind the bearer to concentrate
harder on comporting him/herself with honor than on merely winning, and to
remind the giver to comport her/himself so as to deserve the honor of being
fought for.  The giver of a favor may properly demand its return either at
the end of the mutually agreed period of its bestowal, or when s/he
believes the bearer has behaved dishonorably.  Similarly, the bearer may
insist on the return of the favor if s/he thinks the giver has behaved
dishonorably.  Like fealty, the obligation is mutual.

My lord Yaakov, good luck to you and your lady in this noble venture..

