	The word Wm is searching for is "scholarship", not "science" -- in
American English, "science" means Physics, Chemistry, and the disciplines
which use numbers.  The Liberal Arts -- History, Ethnography, and
Literary Criticism use an entirely different methodology -- developed and
refined in the few centuries since the Rennaisance -- to come to valid
conclusions about their areas of study.

	One of the chief techniques used by the liberal arts is to insist
that arguements be based on the study of _ORIGINAL SOURCES_ -- not
second-hand accounts of the O.S.s, not descriptions of what someone told
you about hearing someone say about them . . . etc.  The original sources
of the accounts of the "witchburnings of the Inquisition" are almost
certainly in Latin, with some perhaps in the various languages of the
time.

	I can hack my way through Latin (with a pony :-), but I certainly do
not have access to the originals (it's 5,000 miles and several $k from
here to Europe).  I cannot therefore judge the exact numbers, but the
tertiary sources I have read (scholarly histories of the Middle Ages)
agree with Wm's estimate of _thousands_, not _millions_.

	Perfectly ordinary wars in the Middle Ages killed morte people than
all of the Inquisition's idiocy -- the Rhine River actually ran red with
spilled blood several times during the 30 Years' War.  Julius Caesar
(himself a Pagan, note) killed more pagans during his conquest of Gaul
than the Inquisition ever saw people.

	That the methods of the Inquisition were cruel, capricious, and
terrible, there can be no doubt -- but so was "ordinary" justice in those
days.  Trial by torture was accepted as an ordinary technique of
jurisprudence until just about the end of our era.  Just as corporal
punishment is on the decline in the 20th Century, but increasingly common
as we look backward, so have the "accepted" means of interrogation
changed over time.  

	Elizabeth I of England had several men convicted of treason 
"Hanged, then cut down whilst still living, their bowells burnt
before their fayces, and thence drawn and quartered, and their partes
displayed in the diverse cities of England."  This was not considered
cruel and unusual punishment in the late 1500s -- it is now.

	I live in California, the Granola state (lots of fruits & nuts, but
mostly flakes), and I know several of the authors of the books mentioned.
The are not "scholars" in the sense that Wm is talking about -- they are
_polemicists_ (propagandists) for a particular outlook.  Starhawk, for
instance, makes no pretence of coming from a "long historical tradition"
of withches -- she started life as a nice Jewish girl from Brooklyn, and
has made up her "craft" as she went along.  (Her original coven was
called "Compost" :-).

	Zee Budapest is an outright radical feminist, whose attitude is that
anything done or said by men must be crap.  Her writings reflect this
attitude, much more than they reflect any "unbiased" view of what
happened in history.

	Robert Graves' scholarship is impeccable -- but he says explicitly in
"the White Goddess" that it is a work of _poetry_ and not _history_ --
I've read it two or three times.  He speaks of symbols and meanings, not
of things which happended in a concrete universe.

	That all three (and Merlin Stone, Lady Sheba, and the
not-so-anonymous author of the Gardnerian Book of Shadows) speak with the
authentic voice of a _newly-emerging_ spirit of Goddess-consciousness
cannot be denied.  The Earth, Mother Gaia, calls all of us who are open
to a new outlook (Weltanschauung, philosophy) of dealing with the
physical world and the spirit -- one more organic than logical, more
sensual than intellectual.  It is entirely appropriate to the late 20th
Century, after the terrors we have seen arise from the relentless hunger
for power.

	Bitterness, rage, and invective against the "old ways", and
deliberate distortions of fact are Hilter & Goebbels' tools for
destroying the order of the world -- they are _not_ the way of the Craft
or the Lady.  Christ talks of Karma indirectly -- "As ye sow, so also
shall ye reap" -- and almost all of the new traditions agree.  If the
cycle of bitterness and destruction is to be broken in our generation, it
is imperative that we treat each other with respect, and understand that
we, as individuals, cannot have an exclusive lock on Truth and the One
Way -- that route ends with Jim Jones in Guyana, Treblika, Auschwitz, and
the other camps, the Gulag, and ultimately with nuclear war.

	To qoute Lady Sheba's Book of Shadows:  "An' ye harm none, do as ye
will."

