Unto to the folk of the Rialto:
 
Thank you for your advice concerning the Purple Fret recommendation.
I hampered the discussion to the extant that I was trying very
hard not to identify the person.
 
I find on re-reading my posting that I did not mention that
I have had several talks with this person.  The talks were
pretty frank.  On one occasion, this person (who was then a member
of the executive) was spoken to by our senior peer (a knight) and
myself in FRONT of the executive, and told they would have to
curb their public behaviour.  Note, I say public behaviour.
If they want to sleep with half of Canada on their own time,
that's their business.  It is the group's business when
several of our members have been physically harassed (mauled
under pretext of offerring congratulations, etc.), when newcomers
have been driven away because this person acts physically familar
with them under pretext of being medieval (far too often).
 
When this person was rebuked at the executive meeting (firmly,
but with love, the way it is done in a family), they seemed to
understand.  The person phoned most of us afterwards to discuss
it further, and kept saying "it's just the way I am".  I advised
the person not to make the first move with strangers and
acquaintances.  Let them indicate that they wanted to hug or
be touched first.  Unfortunately, my advice was taken for about
two weeks.
 
The only people that will work with this person are a few people
of the same sex who don't have a friend this person has harassed,
people of the opposite sex that are too old for this person's tastes,
and one or two married couples (who will only work with this person
in the company of their spouse, because they are afraid of what
will happen if they are left alone with this person).
 
Why is this person allowed around at all, you might ask.  Well,
we are a pretty tolerant and forgiving bunch.  (Some people
would say stupid)  We don't like to
come down on someone just because they are different.  The person
does have a lot to offer, and accomplishes a lot by themselves,
with their spouse, and with the few people still unoffended.
The spouse is very well liked by the group.
 
The spouse has been talked to, and it didn't work.
 
The person and I have talked very recently, as I think I mentioned,
and they know why they don't have a Fret (they talked, and I
listened--I'm not in the habit of looking for trouble!) and have
reiterated that they have no intention of changing.
 
If I write to the Crown, and bare all, and the award is not given,
the letter will presumably stay in the files.  If a future letter
is written, far more justification will have to be given for
recommending the award.
 
I don't believe that awards have much to do with popularity.
It is true that people who have a habit of making enemies have
a lot of trouble getting awards, especially service awards and
peerages.  I believe that all awards, but these two in particular
take character into consideration.  Similarly, in a good company,
the people promoted to manager have a concern for people, treat
them with respect, and are adept at dealing with customers (the
equivalent of outsiders and newcomers).  Mundane companies blow
it sometimes and promote a turkey.  So does the SCA.
 
I have just realized, as I talked, that if my Barony was a company,
I would give this person meaningful and challenging work, a good
salary, and plenty of encouragement.  But, I would not give them
a promotion until the behaviour towards fellow-employees changed.
 
(Now, if I could just figure out how a Purple Fret applies...)
 
Enid Aurelia
