Date:	Mon, 3 Apr 89 12:25:54 EDT
From:	bnr-public!bulman@bnr-fos.uucp (Jennifer Bulman)
Subject: The colour pink
Message-Id: <89Apr3.132018edt.5458@gpu.utcs.toronto.edu>

Lady Malice writes about the notorious laurel dyeing story.
I heard that story too.  A friend of mine overheard this
person say that they didn't have pink- all the manuscripts
showed pink because the red had flaked off!!
 
I was so annoyed I undertook a series of practical experiments
to prove what I already knew from historical and archaeological
sources.
 
Madder produces a wide variation in shades from baby pink to
dark, brick red.  This is provided you do not ever boil the
dyepot.  Dark, brick red comes from mordanting with alum.
If you boil a madder pot, you get shades from
orange to brown.
The best madder for pink comes from the inside of the root.
 
I have documented the results of my experiments in issue 2 of
Spindle and Distaff (my occasional textile magazine), and I
have entered a knitted baby blanket which was dyed in the wool
pink with madder in Pentathlon.
 
Madder was used by the Egyptians, Greeks and Romans (see A.J.
Forbes, Studies in Ancient Technology for a start, also any
ancient textile collection).  It was forgotten in much of Europe
during the Dark Ages, and rediscovered by the 8th century and
much used until the discovery of aniline dyes in the 1800s.
Madder was one of the two components of turkey red (used on
British solidier's uniforms) The other
was cochineal.  Before cochineal was brought back by the
Spaniards in the 1500s, the Mediterranean equivalent, kermes
(a type of sea snail) was used.  Some Parmelia lichens
when fermented, give
red and purple.  Casselman (Dyeing with Lichens and Moss) discusses
this.  Hrolf Kraki's cloak was dyed with this (he was said to
be as splendid as the Emperor of Byzantium).  The Emperor's
clothes were dyed with murex.  The secret of Tyrrian purple was
so well guarded that it died with the Byzantines.  No-one has
successfully duplicated the process.  I think it must have been
related to how indigo works and if I ever get at some murex...
Tyrrian purple was actually deep red.
 
If anyone is interested in a bibliography for madder or indigo,
let me know and I'll dig it out of the archiver.
 
Speaking of pink things.  The Romans ate beetroot.  Apecius has
several recipes for it.  The early medieval people did not.
If you look at recipes like Joutes, it is clear they were eating
the leaves.  (The recipe for beet pie in Lorna Sass is wrong.)
Turnip leaves were eaten long
before the turnip roots, though there are recipes for turnip root
before there are recipes for beetroot.
 
We have several sources in the late 1500 and 1600's that indicate that
eating beetroot is a novelty.  (See Wilson, Food and Drink in
Great Britain).
 
This would seem to clinch the case for beets.
 
Enid
