Subject: More on favours

In SCA Digest #292 (I think), Yaakov Hamizrachi asked about favours.

Milord: As Awilda Halfdane has said, a favour can be practically anything.  I
have seen chain mail favours, leather favours, ribbons, bits of trim, pieces
of fur (common among the Veassllurds)... anything you can attach to one's garb
or armour.  Often non-fighters receive favours from ladies (and sometimes
ladies get them from lords); it's a token of affection.

Sometimes the etiquette of favours gets strange and complex; if you've been
reading Pikestaff for a few years, you might remember that "Dear Goody" (the
sometime etiquette columnist) received more mail on this subject than any other.

Often a favour says something about the giver; the chainmail favours generally
come from talented armourers.  Some have embroidered initials, the lady's arms
or a symbol that means something to her (one costumer I know put an embroidered
pair of scissors on hers), sayings or fragments of songs or poetry... it all
depends on the meaning and on how much trouble you and your lady want to go to.

I've made four favours in my life and given away three: one to a friend, one
to an old boyfriend, one lasted longer than the romance did, and the fourth
was a piece of ribbon I'd been wearing on my circlet one day.  A lord in
armour came up to me and asked me if I might give him a favour to inspire him
in battle that day, as his lady was unable to attend the tourney.  When he
took off his helm, it turned out to be an old mundane friend of mine who had
joined the SCA without my knowing!

Ladies in the East might consider carrying bits of ribbon with them for the
duration of the next reign.  The soon-to-be-Queen has decreed that no fighter
should enter the lists uninspired.  (Of course, lady fighters should also be
thus honoured...)

