Favors  are tokens of a lady's favor.  They can be anything.  Historically,
knights going into a tourney would go to the lady they admired and ask her for
some token of their favor to carry with them to give them heart and keep up
their spirits.  This was usually improvised, but became rather elaborate as
time went on.  A lady asked for a favor would hand over whatever she could come
up with-a scarf, a veil, a tippet, a ring, even going so far as to rip the
sleeve off her gown.  The fighter wore it tied around his arm or tucked into
his belt.

The Order of the GArter was begun this way: a knight asked the Queen of England
for a favor.  Nothing came to hand, but then she had a bright idea.  She
reached under her skirt and pulled off her garter.  If memoroy serves, there is
an Order of the Buckle in Spain that started much the same way.  

In SCA ladies usually offer favors voluntarily to men they like.  Sometimes men
ask for favors--Crown Tourney usually prompts a rash of favor-gifts.  In the
SCA  ladies usually embroider a piece of cloth which is then worn looped
through the belt.  Some people have even gone so far as to make "battle favors"
and "court favors".  A "battle favor" is something sturdy and compact that
won't get in the way, can be easily washed, and no one's feelings will be hurt
if it gets damaged.  A "court favor" is very elaborate for use on formal
occassions.  

Anybody can give a favor to anybody else.  It means generally that you like the
person.  Ladies who give out favors have usually given favors to several
people.  Men can give favors too, but I have only ever seen it happen once.  

