  About tolerance: I agree! We, and deserve, high standards.
About the demographics of the SCA:   I have a sense of linked subcultures. In
particular, most SCAdians I know seem to be one or more of the following:  SCA,
Pagan folk, SF/Fantasy fannish, Gamers, ComputerJocks/Users, Comic book collec-
tors.In addition, many are in academe, and others are martial artists, although
many more people who follow those disciplines do not partake of the linked sub-
cultures.  Often, members of one interest find others through it, perhaps re-
maining identified through the original one, perhaps redefining themselves with
later exposure.  I will not go into my definition of a working subculture at
this time, although we can discuss it some other time if anyone is interested.
Actually, if I ever decided to finish my Soc/Anthro. degree, I could probably
get a thesis out of this discussion, so please don't steal if...
  Anyway, it seems to me that certain qualities are held in common between mem-
bers of these various groups.  One is creativity.  Another is the ability to
suspend disbelief (it will, too, load...). We mostly share a strong and flexible
sort of intelligence, whatever our formal education.  All of these qualities
would seem conducive to tolerance of each other's differences, as we have toler-
ance for the creations of other authors, artists, programmers, etc.
  Unfortunately, another quality many of us have in common is the experience,
prior to finding our particular entrance to the linked subculture, of being
ostracized as "different".  That, at times, can lead to defensiveness rather
than to the healthier sensitivity to others' plights and variations.  One
hopes that in time, participation in a more accepting and congenial group will
allow those who have been scarred to try again.  I don't know what those who
have been hurt within the group can do except to be patient and more tolerant
than whoever hurt them, and trust that person, too, will heal with time.
