*ALL* of the wine & beer recipes I've seen from period had a phrase
saying that after you mix the ingredients together you

        cover it over with a cloth and let it sit for a few days.

There was no add-the-yeast stage, just let it sit.  And it's exactly
the thing my girlfriend told me to do when she wanted to start making
sourdough.  She told me to mix the ingredients, let it sit out for
a couple of days, and when it starts bubbling to refrigerate it.

Now, there's yeasts floating around us in the air all the time.  So
when we let something sit out it 'catches' any yeast floating around.
This is going to be some rando-yeast that just happens to be floating
by -- unless there's some reason why a particular area would be
concentrated with certain yeasts.  Like, if there's heavy winemaking
activity going on in an area the yeast population will concentrate
itself with wine yeasts.

I doubt if people in period had any idea there was any such thing
as yeast (or for that matter any other micro-organism) and wouldn't
have been able to explain why wine making worked.  Nor would they
have been able to understand why's and wherefore's of cultivating
yeast and making sure you had a pure strain and all.  Wasn't Pasteur
in the 1800's?  And wasn't he the guy who figured this stuff out?


