Date: 31 Mar 89 14:29:38 GMT
From: david@davids.UUCP  (David Herron)
Subject: Book Review: From Vines to Wines
Message-Id: <8903310929.AA00866@davids.UUCP>


Book: From Vines to Wines; the Complete Guide to Growing Grapes
                        & Making Your Own Wine.
Author: Jeff Cox
PBL: Garden Way Publishing
ISBN:    "88-44898 ISBN 0-88266-528-6 (pbk.)"

This printing is 1988, but it was originally published in 1985 by Harper & Row.

Weighing in at 250 pages (approx) this is an amazingly complete book.  It
contains short courses in wine appreciation (and tells you that the real
way to learn is to sign up for real courses), grape growing, and most
importantly wine making.  Each section appears complete, except in the
wine MAKING section I don't remember a section on hints to removing
off tastes.

The writing style is clear and down to earth.  He understands the needs
of a hobbyist for whom wine-making isn't their WHOLE life.  For instance
when talking about barrels for winemaking -- he goes over the exact
reasons for using them (adding "subtle oak flavors to the wine") and
a number of options for getting barrels.  Apparently the best approach
is to send off to France.  But this whole proposition is rather expensive
and besides barrels leak.  So he also talks about using oak chips in
the carboy which is apparently what *he* really does.

Very fair of him, I'd say, to cover all the bases like that even for
techniques he doesn't use himself.

And there's already been one really useful section.  One night after
helping me polish off a bottle of wine my girlfriend got to feeling
very very pained in the stomach.  This had happened once or twice
before after drinking wine and she'd heard that it had something to
do with sulfites.  I'd just bought this book so I looked up sulfites
in it to see what it had to say.

Turned out that professional wine makers use varying degrees of sulfites
and that the author could *taste* sulfites when they were in medium
levels of concentration.  The sulfites come about because of the
common practice for sterilizing wine -- adding hydrogen sulfite.  Some
people, and my girlfriend is apparently one, are overly sensitive to
sulfites and react in exactly the way she did.  Anyway, he goes over
all sorts of issues surrounding sulfites and leaves one almost afraid
to use them :-)

It's a good book and highly reccommended ...

The only lack is that he doesn't have page after page of recipe.  But he
does go over how to come up with recipes on your own.  He carefully
describes the reasons for different sugar & ph levels and how to measure
them to get best effect.



