SSKATZ@pucc.Princeton.EDU (Seth S. Katz):
>Some scholars speculate that the Karites were, in fact,
>a continuation of the Sadducee heresy, a group with identical beliefs
>that existed at about the time of the destruction of the Second
>Temple.  (A secrete cult going underground for centuries, impossible!:)).

To call the Sadducees a heresy, let alone a secret cult, strongly suggests that
we haven't been reading the same histories.

One of the persistant themes of Jewish theological (I use the term imprecisely)
debate over the millenia has been the tension between relatively literal (and
relatively strict) interpretation of Jewish law and a [potentially] more
flexible interpretation.

In the period from the third century BC to the first century AD, this tension
manifested itself in a social/political/religious split into two major
factions/parties.  The Pharisees were (using these terms loosely too) religious
liberals and politically conservative.  That Saducees were religious
conservatives and more amenable to foreign contacts and ideas.  (The Saducees
tended to be upper class, which contributed to both tendencies.)  The Pharisees
won, in the sense that after the destruction of Israel as a state the parties
both disappeared, but the successors of the Pharisees went on to write the
history books.  (In Hebrew school we were taught that the monarchs who supported
the Pharisees were'good' monarchs and those who didn't weren't.  It's
interesting to me that Christians are taught history in such a way as to give
'Pharisee' a negative connotation, and that in that context the term is used to
refer to the scholars rather than to the entire faction.)

The debate about the sufficiency of the written word (versus the reliance upon
the oral tradition which became the Talmud) crops up again and again in Jewish
history.  Making any more of this link between the Kara'ites and the Sadducees
is a bit like calling the first Christians "Early Protestants".

