Unto the people of the Rialto and especially milady Awilda Halfdane Li Kung Lo
sends greetings! I was greatly singed by a recent posting in which you stated
that you were tired of chirurgeons trying to send you to the hospital because
you are handicapped. Your comment was deeply disturbing to me, and you gave no
details. I cannot help being struck by the feeling that one or more of the
following is true:

1) They aren't really chirurgeons, fully warranted, on duty, and bearing the
badge of their office, but generic EMT's standing around.

2) They really *are* chirurgeons, and they need a serious talking to. Did you
discuss any of this with the chirurgeon-in-charge (CIC) at the event, or the
relevent kingdom chirurgeon? Why just complain when you can *make a
complaint*? 

3) You went to a chirurgeon or somebody who cares summoned one. Remember, most
EMS people are trained with an emphasis on immobilization, stabilization, and
transport of a patient with a medical emergency. The assessment and support of
a person with a prior existing and known medical condition does not fall into
that category, unless a medical emergency exists. (If it does, see plan A) We
are not insured, trained, or licensed for that, and in many cases, what would
appear to be common sense supportive measures to a good samaritan are illegal
to us, and may represent professional misconduct/malpractice. Often our only
response is to say, "If this is an emergency, we'll get you to a hospital. If
it isn't, I think you should go home;you don't look well."

4) You *didn't* go to or summon a chirurgeon, and they are trying to be
helpful. You need to say,"I have a well known medical problem. I do not
require your assistance at this time. Thank you for your concern." It is also
polite to tell the CIC what your problem is. If it becomes a medical emergency
at a later point, valuable time will be saved.

5) You are stubborn, and you persist in going to events when you are really in
no shape to, because it is very important to you. Remember, you have not
cornered the market on stubborness in this outfit, and it is *your right* to
be stubborn. If your brothers and sisters (and the chirurgeon) seem
exasperated, remember we still love you-you are family.

