gentles, whether handicapped, chirurgeons, or observers who can add
perspective to the interaction between chirurgeons and handicapped people. If
we think your perception is slanted, we'll try to explain our position to you,
so you will understand us better, and make better use of the services we
offer. If the problem is with chirurgeons, we can talk to them about it, and
try to improve our performance by understanding *your* position better. If the
problem is in the structure, we'll address that problem, perhaps benefitting
everybody. Feel free to post or write me email directly.
        I can't tell you how touched I was by your comments on what the SCA
means to you, maybe I can touch you for just a minute, and you can see things
through my eyes:
        I have been awakened at 4:00AM to deal with the hypochondriac who was
having *another* anxiety attack. (Yes, I really do carry a teddy bear in my
jump kit...) I have been bled on in court garb because of ya-hoos playing with
knives. I've done an *entire war* (Pennsic XVI) where I never had one meal
that was not interrupted by a medical problem. (only one was an actual
emergency) I have been ignored by the marshall when I tried to pull a fighter
out of combat, only to spend 2 hours transferring him to the hospital an hour
and a half later, needlessly. I've been bitten by a drunk, and taken the blood
pressure of an abused, panicked woman clutching a razor sharp
broadsword,biting into her hands. I've spent 45 minutes trying to talk a
backboarded fool with a broken back into letting us transfer him to the
hospital, so he wouldn't have to live in a wheelchair forever. I've spent
countless unpaid hours and given away hundreds of dollars worth of free
medical equipment, and I can tell you that I don't do it because I love
medical emergencies, working for free on my time off, or because of the
wonderful feeling of power it gives me. I do it because I can't say no, you
are all my loved ones.
On the upside, I've seen the gratitude of the parents of a little girl whose
appendicitis was properly diagnosed, and seen her live to grow up. I've seen a
woman in anaphylactic shock saved by the prompt response of unpaid doctors,
nurses and paramedics, and I've seen the teddy bear work! I've had the
pleasure and honor of working with the finest volunteer paramedic team in the
world, and I would trade it for *nothing*.
        Please remember that when you make a comment about a group, it gets
their attention, and you can always get mine by bashing chirurgeons.

