     I doubt that grabbing territory has much to do with it.  I suspect
that the main factor involved is seniority: when a new group is started
in a pre-existing group, most of the territory is likely to be left to
the old group (this seems to be the case with the Barony-Marche).  Also,
people who live a long way from the main center of a group's population
and activity are likely to split off and form a new group anyway.  This
just recently happened in Nithgaard.  Besides, even if you have a large
territory, that doesn't mean that you can recruit new members outside of
the central area(s) of your group.
     I agree that there should be a better way to divide up territory.  I
suspect that the current method is only used because of the way in which
the membership requirements are enforced.  Personally, I think that they
should do away with zip code boundaries for groups below the Kingdom (and
perhaps Principality) level, let people join any group they like, and not
go to the trouble of checking membership levels unless a group seems to
be in serious trouble.  But then, I don't know how this would work if it
were done this way.

