Subject: yeast

i too, have seen ale yeast required in recipies. there are few pre-16th 
century recipies for bread, but there are several 14th and 15th c. recipies 
for batter, which call for yeast (some times confusingly spelled zest) or ale 
yeast.  
The romans (i am here paraphrasing from the work of Mistress Marian of 
Edwinstowe) used a sour-dough culture, and noted that the barbarians (i.e. the 
germanic tribes to the north) used ale yeast and got a much lighter bread.  
(they were also using a harder wheat)

in anycase it is good to remember that they were not using packets of dry 
yeast but a live culture, tossing in pints of ale barm (barm=yeast culture) at 
a time.  you could buy your barm, or you could keep your own.  Part of the 
pantry furnishings in many american houses was a yeast drawer, which was a 
small drawer lined with porcelin.

Ask your local brewers for a bottle of nice lively ale and toss it into your 
next batch of bread, substituting it for the liquid, or, drink the ale and 
just use the dregs in place of normal yeast.  It wont be nearly as fast as 
commercial yeast, but it will rise (eventually), and makes a nice loaf.

We once found the last inch of a jug of cider burbling away to itself on the 
back steps and used it as yeast--it made a dense but perfectly edible loaf of 
bread and it smelled wonderfull while it baked.

We in Carolingia (cambrige food-coop; they also have cubebs) can obtain two 
kinds of wheat, the red-grained hard wheat and the paler, plumper soft wheat. 
American flour is made of hard wheat, it takes much more liquid than european 
or middle-age flour.  The soft wheat has (i think) a better flavor.  The 
romans and the middle agers had several kinds of wheat, including spelt which 
is a variety of wheat of which i know none of the properties exept that its 
yeild is far smaller than that of the favored wheat.  Does any one know more 
about varieties of wheat as used in the midle ages, and whether they are still 
available?  Also, millet and vetches were both major crops, but i don't know 
how they were used...

