Date: Thu, 30 Mar 89 14:26:44 PST
From: Kevin Karplus <karplus@azuki.ucsc.edu>
Message-Id: <8903302226.AA06298@azuki.ucsc.edu>
Subject: metallurgy of mail armor, mead recipes

Some metallugical analyses of rings from mail shirts have been made (I have
to dig out my notes and find that article again!).
In all the rings sampled (from several different periods and places), the
metal was wrought iron (almost pure iron, carbon content far lowest than
the softest "mild" steel now available).
There is also no evidence for case hardening of mail, though it would be 
expected to strenghten it significantly.

The author of the article concluded that the mail makers valued ease of 
manufacture over strength of the resulting mail, as reasonably high quality
steel was used for other purposes (plate armor, weapons, ...). 
Certainly modern mailmakers prefer ease to strength, as they don't even bother 
riveting the rings.  
Wrought iron would be MUCH easier to punch and rivet than mild steel, as it
doesn't work-harden nearly as much.



For making mead, you should choose the yeast according to the type of mead you wish to make.  I use ale yeasts for "quick" fizzy meads, with about the strength of beer, and wine yeasts for stronger meads.
My best batch of mead was a strong dessert wine using a white wine yeast.
I fermented it for over a year and aged it in bottles for at least another two
years.
If people are interested, I'll try to dig up the recipe.

