Message-Id: <607305831/kee@A.NL.CS.CMU.EDU>

Lord Kwelland's geography appears to be a little out of date.  There
are TWO shires in the general area of the Midrealm to which he refers.
The older one is Dearnheld (Athens, OH), founded in the early years of the 
Society (A.S. IV?  I am not sure) and it was there that I joined the SCA 
in A.S. X.  The newer one is Mugmort (Logan/Lancaster OH), formed around 
A.S. XV, as I recall (I was at the Court where it was officially
chartered.)  For all I know, there could be yet another forming between 
the Columbus area and Mugmort, since I haven't kept up with all the
changes in the SCA geography of the Columbus area in the past 10 years.

Now, as to West Virginia, Lord Kwelland's point that there are lots of
possibilities for carving up the place are well-taken, and have been
considered in the discussions of the issue.  (I speak here as a member
of the "Principality Committee" which was formed a year and a half ago
to try and bring the Principality into reality.)  But I can't help but
feel that putting the issue on the level of "WV is a problem, what can
we do?" or as I crassly put it above, "carving up the place" is kind of
rude.  (I speak here as one who was born and raised in Charleston, WV.)
I don't know of any SCA member in WV who has net access, aside from the
gentle who works for IRS in Martinsburg (I'm sorry, I can't remember
his name!) and he is probably an Atlantian, since he's located in the
extreme Eastern Panhandle of the state.  So if anyone is wondering why
these folks aren't speaking up for themselves on the Rialto, that's
probably why.  I think if they were present, they would say that the
discussion as it stands is not very mindful of them as SCA members;
that the geographical puzzle posed by the Principality formation is 
of far more interest to the Rialto than any consideration of what
the members in WV want their own SCA future to look like.

Fortunately the East Kingdom Seneschale wants to know what they want.
The decision currently rests with them, and they have several options,
and it looks like they may well ask to be re-polled.  The fact that the
BMDL voted to go with the Principality has changed the equation.
Re-polling may or may not reveal much of a change, or a difference
between what the southern part of the state says and what the northern
part of the state says, but I think it would be a wise option.  WV is
isolated both in SCA and mundane reality, and I think that poor
communication prior to the original polling may have led to votes being
cast on the basis of too little real information.  Now that more effort
has been made to talk it over, a re-poll could settle the issue in a
fairly clean way.

If it doesn't, then BMDL will probably cede ZIP codes to make a thin
bridge to the body of the East.  I would regard this as being a good
temporary solution (but if it led to a stable situation there would not
be much reason to change it.)  It would give things time to settle out,
and give the various groups in WV time to decide on an individual basis
whether or not they wanted to join another Kingdom.  There are good
points and bad points to all the proposed solutions, but I think that
the people who have to live with the consequences are in the best
position to decide what will work (given decent communication with the
East Kingdom Seneschale, with any other Kingdoms involved, and between/within 
the groups themselves.)

[I think that the "land bridge" idea is essentially equivalent to not
worrying about whether or not the East is contiguous.  It's a hack.
It would work for the foreseeable future, but if in future years a
shire wanted to form in the land bridge area, it could lead to bitter
dispute.  That is the main reason I think that if a land bridge is
resorted to, it should be thought of as temporary.  Otherwise it really
is a meaningless hack that simply removes a bureaucratic obstacle.
West Virginia is geographically and culturally isolated and a thin line
of ZIP codes isn't going to change that.  Only good communications and
good will on all sides can bring the shires there into mainstream SCA
life.]

Montani Semper Liberi!

--Marian Greenleaf (past Seneschale, BMDL, current E.K. MoAS)
