Greetings from Hal Ravn:
 
Godfrey de Shipbrook writes:
>   Out of curiosity: assuming that the links for mediaeval chain mail were
>made in the same fashion as they are today (ie, winding wire onto a mandrel,
>or variations on that theme), how was the wire originally produced?  And how
>strong/reliable was it?
 
Can't really say how the links were made--but how the wire was made
depends on period.  Wire-drawing dies were invented in the 1500s.
Prior to that, wire was made by hammering out a sheet of metal, cutting
it into strips, and hammering the strips into wire.  All-in-all, a *very*
labor-intensive project.  (Which explains why mail was expensive--even before
you worry about the work on the links!)  This wuold tend to produce rather
short pieces of wire, so winding may not be too efficient.  
 
