Wire drawing is MUCH older than the 13-th century---going back to at least the
10th century.  By the 13th century, wire-drawing was a separate guild in
parts of Germany--separate from the mail makers.  They bought their wire just 
as we do.  The main improvements in the 13th and 14th century were power 
equipment for wire-drawing, replacing the hand-drawn wire of previous centuries.
 
I have NEVER seen mail with triangular cross-section, but I have heard of 
D-shaped wire formed by drawing through a v-shaped notch (with a rounded bottom)
that had a crossbar to establish the diameter.  
 
I'm sorry I don't have my sources here at work, but if someone challenges me on this, I'll dig them up.
 
I DO WISH there was a decent book on the history of technology.  Unfortunately,
the "history of science" people all seem to believe that only theories matter,
so we may never see a history of practical technology.  Even more specialized
history (such as a history of metal working) would be valuable.  I have
seen some decent work in the history of textiles--perhaps someone who has
done more library work than me could point me to a good history of metal 
working?
 
