Subject:  Awards/behavior
 
Greetings!
 
Regarding the question of awards and behavior:  this is certainly not a unique
situation; I think it must arise in all Kingdoms.  Personally, I think it
perfectly proper to consider the behavior of a gentle in recommending/
considering that gentle for an award.  In the case of a possible Peerage, the
area of behavior should be, and is, given considerable importance.
 
It also depends on the award, though.  In the case of non-armigerous awards
and awards which carry AoA's, I have no problem with "well, he/she may be
utterly obnoxious, but they've done the work..."  Upon hitting the Grant of
Arms level, I start to give the area of behavior more weight.
 
First I consider whether the behavior of the individual in question is merely
annoying, or downright discourteous and/or harmful.  If I find that I lean
towards the former, then I try to look at whether or not the work the gentle
has done has been hampered by their behavior.  If not, and if the merely-
annoying behavior is something intrinsic to their nature, then I will tend to
go ahead and write the recommendation.
 
In the latter case however, I find that I often come to the conclusion that
work accomplished can indeed by offset by damage done to others.  It takes an
awful lot to convince me to write a recommendation for someone who injures
others _via_ their poor behavior.  We are *all* expected to live up to minimum
standards of courtesy in the Society, after all.
 
In an extreme case, such as seems to be with the instance which started this
whole discussion, I personally couldn't write a recommendation for a Kingdom-
leve/GoA-level award in good conscience.  But, neither could I let the
situation go on indefinitely without telling the individual what the problem
was:  I do beleive everyone has the right to be levelled with, as it were.
 
One thing that must be realized and accepted, regardless of what one thinks is
the right thing to do in such an instance as this, is that once one hs done
all one can, one shouldn't worry about it further.  If, for instance, the
gentle has been told in no uncertain terms, that their behavior is
unacceptable (and, P.S. that's why they don't get any recognition) and their
behavior fails to change, then hey-- you've done what you can; it's now
*their* decision.  If they decide not to change their behavior, it's their
problem, and their loss.  The idea of laying out the situation to the Crown
and leaving it for Them to figure out, while viable, doesn't resolve the
situation.  Nor does it make the Crown's life any easier:  they will be facing
the same quandry you are.  And, the ill-behaved individual may still not know
they've got a problem (although that doesn't seem to apply in this particular
case).
 
I want to add to the above, that I do not think there is anything *wrong* with
writing the Crown and laying out the entire situation.  I just think it dodges
the issue a bit.
 
I also think it important to note that the thought of giving someone an
"Attaboy!" for progess made, such as was described in a recent posting, is a
*great* idea, and an essential one.  Positive behavior deserves positive
reinforcement (Pavlov had a point, y'know...), and that's part of what awards
are for.
 
One more thing before I close:  can we **PLEASE** leave off the religion
topic, already?  Ain't it about time we started talking about the proposed new
_Corpora_?
 
Thanks for your attention.
 
 
