Date: Tue 28 Mar 89 02:23:54
From: "]ke Eldberg" <CONS.ELF@AIDA.CSD.UU.SE>
Subject: Witch-craft
Message-ID: <890328022354.10.CONS.ELF@AIDA.CSD.UU.SE>
 
I thank milord Li Kung Lo for his comments, and hereby disagree with them.
 
Milord, your example from the realm of language is irrelevant. The develop-
ment of languages is indeed erratic, but it has little to do with the life
expectancy of traditions that are handed down orally in a group of people.
The latter is certainly not subject to any firm "laws", but it can be
examined and has been so in the field of "family history" - a subject of
study at Swedish universities. We have made the observation that isolated
religious traditions normally don't survive very long. I maintain that
the notion of a Viking religion, secretly handed down intact to our time,
is absurdly unlikely if we judge from what we know of how these things 
usually work.
 
I have read a couple of books on modern paganism, with titles that sounded
very similar to those you refer to (sorry, they were loans from the library
and I cannot quote them since I don't have them). My impression was that they
were full of wishful thinking. The writers, themselves pagans (or sympathisers)
were using every means at their disposal to prove a pagan version of history,
i.e. they were interpreting facts to fit into their pre-meditated thesis.
 
Perhaps I chose the wrong books? But ever since witchcraft became popular among
students, there has been a demand for this type of literature, and I think I
see a pattern here. They make themselves out to be re-interpreting history and
correcting the Christian prejudices contained in the "official" academic
history-writing. Unfortunately, it is easy to write a book which gives a
scholarly impression on the average reader, even if the contents is bullshit.
The books I read were obviously based on a desire to legitimize paganism by
arguing its ancient heritage and exaggerating its importance in Christian times.
 
You are perfectly right that the old Norse paganism was not an organized
ryligion like christianity or judaism. It had no creed, no official collection
of dogma. Traditional religion probably varied a lot between regions and
even households. The same thing is true about all "old" religions in Europe.
There were various sets of traditions that interacted, Celtic and Germanic,
etcetera. We can identify a Norse religion as distinct from continental
Germanic religion, and so on. But the exact contents are not known.
 
What we *do* know is that most of the beliefs have been lost. We know of many
myths that existed but whose contents are now unknown. We can trcce names
of deities in place-names, but we know nothing about them except for their
names. Now, if you claim that modern paganism can trace its roots to the
Dark Ages, I won't argue with that. Religious phenomena such as magic and
witchcraft are virtually timeless. What I refuse is the notion that there
existed standard set of religious beliefs and practices which have been handed
down intact through the ages.
 
Further, I would like to challenge your statement that "5-7 million people
were tortured and put to death as witches by the Christian churches of
Europe and their secular representatives" between the years 1450 and 1670.
 
First of all, we should make a difference between those who were executed
by the inquisition and those who were burned in the great popular witch-
hunts. The inquisition was a sualified court (though of course not up to
modern standards), and it examined all cases thoroughly. If you look at the
protocols which remain to us, you will be surprised at how fair and even
rational they were. Also, recent studies have revealed that the number of
death sentences passed by the inquisition were far fewer than most people
believe. 
 
Most of the burnings were not the results of activities of the church, but 
of popular superstitions and mass-hysteria which erupted from time to time
throughout the renaissance. It clearly had extatic and mass-psychotic traits,
very interesting for psychologists but difficult for historians to explain.
The Church in Sweden actively opposed these persecutions and played a major
role in having them stopped. 
 
Your estimation of the number of killed is one of the highest I have seen.
In fact, nobody knows how many were killed, but *most* scholars make far
lower estimations, perhaps 100,000 to 300,000. We cannot know for sure, but
your figures are extreme.
 
Second, it is well known that those who were executed as witches were usually
*not* pagans, witches or any such thing. They were just people who were
different in one way or another, and became victims of popular xenophobia.
Modern research has noted the tendency to burn people who did not conform
to the normal mode of life in one way or another. Living in a house slightly
apart from the other houses of the village, or being a single woman, or
having too many children or too few children, or having too good teeth
or a swarthy complexion, or any such detail, could be enough to arouse the
suspicions of the bigots and hysteric xenophobes.
 
I never said that violation of civil rights were defendable. I was merely
trying to point out that negative attitudes toward witches aren't neces-
sarily caused by bigotry. I see every reason to condemn those who persecute
others for their religious beliefs. But I see no reason for condemning anyone
for putting an iron bar across his door if he knows that his neighbour openly
professes to worship satan and to being an evil and hostile person. And in
normal, every-day English, that is exactly what a witch is.
 
Well, now we have flogged this dead horse quite a lot. Let's sell it to
Mac Donald's so they can make hamburgers of it. (Truly pagan food, you
know, horsemeat...)
 
William de Corbie
