Date: 30 Mar 89 01:44:03 GMT
From: joshua@paul.rutgers.edu  (Joshua Mittleman)
Subject: Landed Titles
Message-Id: <Mar.29.20.44.03.1989.28073@paul.rutgers.edu>
 
 
Good gentles,
 
As the East moves toward division into Principalities, I have given
some thought to landed nobility, feudalism, and the SCA.  My
conclusion has been that we don't have enough of any of these.  There
are very few examples in the SCA of a feudal structure more than
thgree layers deep: King, Noble, Retainer or King, Baron, Canton
Seneschal, Canton member is about as complicated as it gets.
 
Does anyone know of any more extensive examples?
 
It seems to me that we should have more feudalism, if we really want
to recreate medieval society, and that the SCA would greatly benefit
from it.  To that end, I have a (heretical) suggestion for discussion:
Landed Counts. 
 
In many parts of the Twelve Kingdoms, there are alliances formed among
neighboring shires and baronies, which have varying size and
formality.  For example, several shires in the southern reaches of the
East have for several years called themselves "The Mountain
Confederation".  Much of the area now forming the Principality of the
Lakes was for years known as The Western Marches.  The Baronies of
Nova Caesaria have banded together as The Wetlands Alliance.  These
alliances fight together, and often act together as a political unit.
They ARE feudal structures in the SCA, and it might be nice to have a
formal way to recognize them.  
 
I offer the possibility that several neighboring branches could, by
mutual agreement, have the Crown appoint a Landed Count to act as
their ruling noble.  He might hold court and give awards, as a Baron
does, but would rank higher than a Landed Baron.  All baronies and
shires under his sway would owe fealty to him, and he would swear
fealty to the Crown.
 
Of course, Landed Counts should rank below Royal Counts, just as Royal
Dukes in period & modern England outrank other Dukes.  The parallel,
in my mind, is perfect.  There should be no problem with confusion: We
have no problem remembering which Barons are enfeifed, and should have
even less problem with the few Counts created in this new way.
 
What do you'all think?  Is it worth pursuing?  Will the royal peers
scream & yell too much for it to work?  Could we solve that problem by
using some other title, such as "Marquis"?
 
I look forward to your ideas.  Good cheer!
 
	Arval.
