The latest Tournements Illuminated had some Epistles to the Editor I wish to
respond to.  In particular, I wish to respond to the gentle who said that
people who were ill or injured ought to do the "chivalrous" thing and stay
home, rather than bothering their friends with their problems.  I think the
gentle was referring to people who are temporarily disabled, not permanently or
lengthily disabled, but all the same, I've seen the same attitude all too
frequently.  (I am tired of chirugeons trying to send me to the hospitable
because I am a disabled person).

I am a handicapped person, a fact which has led me to suffer a lot more
discrimination than being pagan has.  Being pagan runs the risk of maybe
getting beat up by redneck Christians, being handicapped means that
well-meaning people keep trying to run my life and prevent me from having a
normal life.

Yes, handicapped people in the SCA cannot do many of the things other people
do.  But in the SCA we need all kinds of people with all kindss of skills and
interests.  I will never scrub the floor after an event, and its been a while
since I've been able to serve one, but who else is going to spend the morning
carving apples into little birds for the Royal Lunch?  And who else is
organizing children's classes when nobody else wants the burden?

yes, the smart thing would be for me to stay home and take care of myself.  But
I am trapped at home for days upon end with no social life to speak of.  I am
willing to pay the price of physical pain in order to see people and talk to
them, to make myself useful.  Human beings need social contact more than they
need security. And since I cannot work at a paying job, I am doing things for the
SCA.  Human beings need to feel useful and appreciated.  

It's really very easy to accomodate a handicapped person.  If we can cope with
fighters and their excess of baggage while traveling, or parents with children,
or cooks who drive themselves crazy in the kitchen, we can certainly cope with
handicapped people.  

Yours in service,
