Re:  Western use of Thrusting Tips and Shield Size.

The West (I believe) has allways allowed thrusting tips.  At least
for the last 10 years, I think since forever.  However, while they
have been common, they have never been "the norm".  i.e. most
fighters don't use them, but if you get to 6-7th round at a Crown
List you probably had to fight at least once vs. a thrusting tip.

We don't use the "touch you're dead" school of face thrusts (seems
kind of silly to me).  I don't think you'll ever get Westerners to
accept shots that hit the bars on their help, that are 3" away from
their face.  Basically, a thrust needs to be "solid", but not a
strong as a normal attack.

Also, most of the thrusting tips are attached to shortswords or
greatswords, etc., but not usually to a broadsword.  Attaching a
thrusting tip to a broadsword causes it to become "less useful",
i.e. balance gets thrown off, etc.

Even in wars, where A LOT of thrusting tips are found, they are very
rarely attached to broadswords, but you will find A LOT of
shortswords, axes, maces, polearms, pikes, etc., with them.

As to fighting quality:  (warning: don't take this personally)  My
opinion is that the problem stems from the training.  Basically,
TRAIN YOUR NEW FIGHTERS WITH BROADSWORDS (WITHOUT THRUSTING TIPS),
and don't let them have thrusting tips until they are well versed in
the basics.  Just like you don't teach "the rap" until you have
taught "the snap".

This won't stop new fighters from putting thrusting tips on their
weapons, but if all your training is directed at using "the edge"
they will quickly learn to leave them off, until you show them how
to use them.  With Squires, and other members of a Knight's
Household, this shouldn't be a problem, just say NO.

Here in the West (or at least in the Mists) most new fighters get
trained with broadswords and 24" round shields.  After they have
been trained in the basics (about the time the round shield breaks)
they should know enough about fighting to decide what weapon/shield
they want to specialize in.  As I said, there isn't anything
stopping a new fighter from using a thrusting tip, but they will
have trouble finding anyone to teach them how to use it.

Re:  "Basic Training" of new fighters.  In the Mists, new fighters
are usually trained in groups.  Starting with "slow work" until they
have armor built, and then progressing through various stages of
training.  The new fighters are basically "segregated" from the
experienced fighters, unless one of the experienced fighters is
training one of them.  i.e. the trainees are at one end of the
fighter practice, and the experienced fighters at the other.

This allows the experienced fighters "to avoid" training new
fighters (on any specific day), if they want.  And, also, keeps the
trainees from being "pounded" on.  Many of the experienced fighters
will spend part of practice with the trainees, and then move to the
other end, to fight "tough" opponents.

This may only work as the "BART Bash" practice on Thursdays usually
has a lot of fighters (i.e. 20) on a good day, so it can basically
be two fighter practices.  Tuesdays, at "BART", is basically for new
fighters, and is more of organized "training" (with fewer
experienced fighters).  Also, on Tuesdays and Sundays, we have the
"Mission College" fighter practice, which is similiar to BART, but
smaller.

Also, there have been true "newbie classes" held on off days, which
are strictly for teaching basics.  The classes vary depending on the
teacher (i.e. limited class size, etc.).

I would be interested in hearing how training is done in other
places.  Especially, those places with radically different fighting
styles (i.e. you guys up in An Tir, I've been to some of your
fighter practices.  But everyone else hasn't.).  Enough of this.

Re:  Shield sizes.  I've allways thought limiting shield sizes was
silly (similiar the limiting thrusting as silly).  The "official"
rules (whatever that means) allready limit shields in that the can't
be constructed using modern materials that give "excessive
advantage", i.e. clear plastic shields, etc.  This "rule" could
reasonably be used to limit shields that have too low a "density",
i.e. wieght/square foot.

One of these days I'm going to build a tourney legal stretched
leather shield, to see how much it weighs, and how it works.  But it
will be a while.

In the West, which has no limitations on shield size, the most
common shields (for tourneys) are:

        1)  Heaters:  Size:  Approx 22-24" wide by 32-36" tall, some
        curved, some flat.  (I may not have the size exactly right
        since I don't use one.)
        2)  Round Shields:  Size:  24" (some variance, but most
        round shields in the west are 24")
        3)  "Radnor Rounds":  Size:  24" by 24".  (there is some
        variance, usually in length)  A "Radnor Round" is square on
        the top, and round on the bottom.  i.e. take a 24 by 24
        square, and cut the two bottom corners off, round, but leave
        the top two as is.  The style is similiar to "agressive"
        round shield, i.e. punch blocking, not rotating.  The shield
