Subject: Chainmail Question

Originally the wire for chainmail was constructed in the same manner
as anything else made of iron or steel, it was hammer forged by a 
blacksmith.  I believe the wires were usually triangular in cross-
section.  That is alot easier to form on a forge than a round cross-
section.

At some point they developed the process of drawing wire.  This is done
by pulling a bar of metal through progressively smaller holes in a
'draw plate', annealing the metal as necessary to maintain it's maleability,
till the wire has reached the desired size.  I think the process of
drawing out wire was developed in Germany in the 13th or 14th Century.
(It's been a while since I read about this.)

