In article <2485@lindy.Stanford.EDU>, AR.SEG@forsythe.stanford.edu
 (Steven E Goodman) says:
>popularity, popularity.  I always thought awards weren't supposed to
>be popularity contests?  But that seems to be the way things work
>Etienne d'Argent           AKA    Steven Goodman
(Nota Bene: some others also referred to the "popularity" issue; this is
just what I chose to quote as an example.)

     The way I see it, the "popularity contest" situation is where it all
depends on how many friends you have to recommend you.  Nobody should ever
recommend someone for an award just because that person is their friend,
and no deserving person should be left out just because they don't have a
lot of friends - except for the Order of the Life of the Party ;-).  But
in the case of "Lord Gunther de Grab," what is relevant is not how many
friends he has, but rather how many enemies he has made, and how he has
made them.  This is NOT just a question of popularity.
     I think that anyone who is to be inducted into any order should be
willing and able to meet a standard of conduct such that they will not be
a disgrace to that order.  This is especially important for the Patent
Peerages, but it should be a consideration for any award.  And awards are
not just for what people do, but also for how they do it.
     Let me consider this in a different way: people get awards not for
what they do, but for what they are.  For instance, if someone is willing
to study a period art/science with an open mind and share their knowledge
and their skills with an open heart, then that person is a good candidate
for the Order of the Laurel.  Their classes, arts projects, or whatever
are only the results of their attitude.  And when an award is given, it
indicates respect for its recipient, not just for their accomplishments.
So I think that it is reasonable to consider how someone behaves (at least
when their behavior is exceptionally good or bad) in deciding whether or
not they should get an award.
     On the other hand, I think it's okay to be somewhat relativistic in
this respect, so that even if someone's behavior/attitude leaves a lot to
be desired, it could be overlooked if it is generally tolerable, and if it
is actually a remnant of a worse problem which they have made considerable
progress in curing themselves of (what an ugly sentence - I hope it at
least says what it means ;-) ).

