	{ I wondered when this was going to come up . . . }

	Sorry, m'lord, but the analogy doesn't apply -- unlike paganism,
Judaism was and is a primarily _written_ tradition -- without the Torah,
there is no Judaism.  The sects of Judaism that lacked, lost, or rejected
the Torah, Mishnah, and Gemara died out within 3 generations (or became
Christianity :-).

	From the time of the fall of the Temple to this day, the way a Jewish
male becomes a man -- recognized as an active part of the Community of
Israel -- is to stand in front of the congregation and _READ_ from the
Torah.  (Carping about the frequent practice of "learning the sounds" and
"memorizing without understanding" aside -- it is the _reading_ that is
the central issue.

	Judaism preserved the ideal of literacy through the black night of
the European Dark Ages, and it is to the Jewish scholars of Iberia that
we owe our knowledge of almost all of Classical thought and writing.
Vivant!

	Literacy was fairly uncommon in Classical times, damned rare in any
culture outside of Rome and Greece, and almost unheard-of north of the
Alps.  Where native writing systems _did_ exist, they were the secret
province of a priesthood, and definitely _not_ passed down in families.

	Such priestly communities as presented political opposition to the
Romans were systematically hunted down and destroyed -- Druids in
Britain, for instance -- and _nothing_ survives.  The Church did the same
after 900 A.D., for the same reasons, and with the same effects.

	Native oral traditions require the active and enthusiastic support of
a living community of a certain size to continue -- when the community
shrinks below a certain size, the religion dies.  On the other hand, a
_written_ tradition needs only one person in each generation, together
with a book, to survive.
