Message-Id: <8903280248.AA02487@ti.com>
Date: Mon, 27 Mar 89 20:40:36 CST
From: evans@lvips.csc.ti.com (Eleanor J. Evans @ 462-5330)
Subject: connotations of "witch"

>In our language, a witch is an evil creature out of the fairy tales. Together
>with trolls, demons, vampires, werewolves and a whole bunch of other fantasy
>creatures, they are the vehicles of evil in the old sagas. In history, witches
>are women who were accused of being identical in behavior to the witches in
>literature, i.e. satanists, i.e. consciously evil and hostile to people.
 
>That witches are evil is part of the *definition* in all western languages, as
>far as I know.  If you talk about "good" witches, people won't understand what
>you mean. You might as well talk about good rapists, good nazis, good murderers
>or good devils.
 
>[People] ... just happen to speak a language where "witch" is a well-known
>word meaning "evil woman".  It's not *their* obligation to know that there
>is a small group of intellectuals somewhere who have re-defined that word.
 
>William de Corbie

This has been an interesting discussion.  William, I would like to thank
you for your comments.  I have found them on this and other issues to be
very thought-provoking.

I'm afraid I have to disagree with your viewpoint in this instance.
Witches have been more frequently evil, true, but this is not universally
the case.  Particularly in this decade people read about sorcery and its
uses in a positive sense.  Most high school level history discussion on
witchcraft (say, in the Middle Ages) does in fact stress that the typical
image of a witch came from the appearance and mannerisms of those women
who lived to an unusual age.

If they survived years of childbirth, women lived longer than men (which
is why witch is identified as female).  With no dental care, the teeth fall
out, leading to the hooked nose and protruding chin effect - it's really
from missing teeth.  Wrinkles and sparse white hair, along with other
signs of age (age is not exactly pretty to the young), complete the look.

Looking so different, and seemingly having cheated death, these women were
off to a bad start.  Add to that a possible crabbiness from being old,
possibly arthritic, and most likely alone in the world.  Now increase that
crabbiness with the natural resentment stemming from being mistrusted due
to age and appearance, and you have a very bad-tempered old lady.  I'm sure
this isn't new to anyone; I'm just saying this is what lots people are
taught.

Any history lesson at the States that covers the Salem witch trials debunks
the accusations of witchcraft that were hurled around so freely.

In other words, lots of people learn (at an impressionable age) that
so-called witches are more likely ordinary misunderstood humans.  (Which
doesn't do much for their reputation in the modern world - people tend
not to believe in them.)

Science fiction and fantasy readers get still another viewpoint - that of
people of real power who use it for good - and who strongly disapprove of
those who use it for evil.  Power in fantasy frequently destroys those who
misuse it.

Even those who don't read SF or fantasy, and who don't cover historical
witchcraft in school still can have their opinions affected - hordes of
people have seen the Wizard of Oz (or read the book - but I counted them
under readers above) - Glenda, remember?  The Good Witch?

Before anyone beats me to it, I will stay that the dictionary definition
of witch (Webster's II, New Riverside University Dictionary, 1984 - my
employer bought it, not me - I'll check my OED when I get home) does say
a woman who practices black magic, not magic.  (Black magic is defined
further along as magic in league with the Devil.)  There are definitions
of other words (magic, for one) which do not imply evil, but this is not
one of them.  (The secondary definition is an ugly, vicious old woman -
in line with the comments on middle ages above.)

I still think that the common understanding of the term is such that
the possibility of good uses of power is part of the word.  That's one
person's opinion.  I think the above examples are enough to show that
the term has not been redefined by a small group of intellectuals somewhere,
but rather by a large mass of population, over a lengthy period of time.

Eleanor MacNaughton
evans@lvis.ti.com

