Message-Id: <8903280249.AA02495@ti.com>
Date: Mon, 27 Mar 89 20:45:00 CST
From: evans@lvips.csc.ti.com (Eleanor J. Evans @ 462-5330)
Subject: expectations, and the disappointment thereof (was RE:  witches)

This is a very long posting.  I apologize for that in advance.  I also
get the list in digest form, so I know how much of a pain it is to
read through pages of a long message that you don't find interesting,
just to get to the next message.  I hope this gets posted at the end
of a digest.

I didn't mean to get this long.  Please let me know if you think the
length or content of this message is inappropriate.  I wax a little
eloquent, but I believe my points are relevant.  (Believe me, I do -
otherwise I wouldn't post this.)

William de Corbie wrote in an earlier posting that those who flaunt their
differences should expect to be ostracized or harassed by the general
populace.  (My apologies to William if I've mistated his views for the
sake of brevity.)

At first, I agreed with his statement.  It really makes a lot of sense.
On further reflection, however, I don't agree that those are realistic
expectations for the cross-section of the US population that reads this
list.  Please note that I'm speaking in generalities here.  I'm sure that
there are US readers who have had personal experience or education that
leads them to these expectations.

For the most part, however, there is a common set of characteristics
which define the members of this group - and those characteristics lead
this group to expect tolerance of other viewpoints.  Please note that
I will only address US demographics - I don't have enough information
about SCA-list readers outside the US.

For example, the US readers on this list are technology freaks - or
married or related or close friends with someone who is.  The evidence?
A computer link which allows the list to be read, and sufficient
familiarity with mailing systems and networks to gain access.

Computer literacy leads us to education - I would bet that most of
the readers on this list are college educated.  Many are still in school,
some are working for companies technologically oriented enough to
provide network access to their employees.  A college education in the
US leads one to the water of tolerance.  Some would say it even tries
to make you drink.

Not only do the professors encourage critical thinking and recognition
of other viewpoints (no flames, please - I'll bet that at least one
professor in the four years that a hypothetical student spends in college
was both motivated to do the above and managed to reach that student),
but also the environment encourages tolerance.  For the first time (for
many students), there are new people around, people who talk differently,
and act differently, and dress differently, and think differently.

Some high school students (or even elementary school, while we're regressing)
get the same kind of exposure.  Racial and cultural mixing takes place
in many schools far more than in the workplace or at home.

For the benefit of those outside the US, elementary school is grades 1-8,
ages 6-13.  High school is grades 9-12, ages 14-17.  Sometimes, grades
7 and 8 or grades 7-9 are called middle school (ages 12-13 or 12-14).  Keep
those pubescent kids off by themselves, where they can't wreak too much
damage.

The standard four years of college after high school (if you went at all)
is losing ground, though is still (I think) the most common.  That would
be ages 18-21.  Lots of people skip grades, or wait a few years between
high school and college, or take off a year or so in the middle, or stretch
it out to 5 years, working alternate terms.  Also, lots of people who
quit school many years ago are returning.  About a third of my college
was older people coming back to school - I was in school with my mother,
for heavens sake.

Sorry for the digression - I just wanted to be clear.  Comparative
scholasticism can be confusing.  So much for education (in case you'd
forgotten the topic by now).

Technophilia and education combine to make it quite likely that most
readers are also science fictions fans.  Nothing (that I can think of
at the moment - anyone want to saw off this branch?) is more intrinsically
tolerant of other viewpoints than science fiction.  It is very hard to
be an SF fan and not begin to sign on to the belief that other viewpoints
are valid.  (It is possible to be a hardened technocrat, only reading
hard SF, and retaining a narrow viewpoint.  It is not common.)

Now look at the effect of SCA membership.  Let's face it, the people
we meet in this group are a little weird.  Lots of members are misfits
in society (don't take this personally - just count the ones you know).
Escapism is one of the reasons people join this group ... and people
escape in lots of different ways.  Group members learn to tolerate and
even enjoy differences in the people around them.

In short :-), the environment of most of the US readers of this digest
has accustomed them to the idea of tolerance for other viewpoints; to
tolerate other people's differences and to expect the same in return.

Those of us who have experienced racism or sexism or "jingoism" or any
other "sectism" have had our expectations lowered (at least a little),
but we are few.  The readers of this group are, for the most part, young.
The civil rights movement and the women's liberation movement have wrought
many changes in our culture, but most of the struggle was before our time -
certainly the more violent aspects.  Blatant discrimination has in large
part gone underground.  Many, if not most, blatant acts are quite illegal.
Subtle discrimination is still quite rampant - but we are not attuned to
seeing it.

We don't see discrimination, and so we don't expect it.  We expect people
to behave in a tolerant and non-discriminatory fashion.  I don't think
this is a bad thing.  People tend to live up to other's expectations of
them.

For examples of the expectations of others affecting behavior, look at
schools - the expectations of the teacher have a bearing on the performance
of the students.  The same kind of effect is visible with parents and
children.  Look at little closer to home, at fellow members of the SCA.
When a group expects chivalry, the individual members of that group
behave more chivalrously.

The first time your expectations are seriously let down, either by the
action of an individual in a serious breach or by the collective actions
of a group in a less serious breach (I mean, it would seem less serious
if it were the act of an individual), the foundation of your world is
shaken.  Nothing has prepared you for unjust behavior on the basis of
a silly category, or on any basis other than personal dislike (which is
accepted if deplored as an individual breach of expectations).

This shattering of your world view is bad enough, without the added
strain that I see in the story that started this discussion.  (I'm sorry,
I wasn't going to follow up, so I didn't save that posting.)

Most of us in the group as described, in addition to the rose-colored
glasses we wear about people, have an optimism about the fairness of
government.  The age group represented doesn't have the same need to
rebel against authority that the previous generation (?) did.  Most of
us consider our government to be in fact of the people, by the people,
for the people.  Those few of us who have had run-ins with various
government branches, such as the IRS, know this is not the case.  However,
because of the collective age of the group, these are again few.

To have the prejudices of one intolerant community and their desire for
oppression and harassment aided and abetted by the very forces we expect
to defend our rights to freedoms of expression and lifestyle is an
absolute nightmare.

To the pagan who posted the tale, and to all those who have experienced
any such form of oppression or harassment ... you have lost your
innocence, and it can never be reclaimed.  I beg of you, please don't
let that loss lower your expectations for other people's behavior.  We
cannot lower the standard of tolerance, or chivalry, for who will raise
it up again?

Eleanor MacNaughton
evans@lvis.ti.com

P.S.  Good thing I didn't have an electric buffer on hand ... or I'd still
be waxing.

