Subject: Thrusting tips and Helmet padding

Thrusting tips:  *very*, no, make that **VERY** common here in Atlantia.
Almost everyone has them on everything possible.  Face thrusts are currently
allowed at all times (tournament and melee), with a touch sufficient
to kill - we aren't trying to rock someone's head back.  The current
king, His Majesty Barry, has asked for comment on banning face thrusts
from single combat - there is an opinion that seems widely held that
the average skill level of fighters has been dropping recently, due
to the overuse of the face thrust - lots of new fighters aren't
learning to throw useful blows because of the perception that a
face thrust is easier to get in.  It also seems to have the advantage
of being proof against rhino-hiding - if it touches your faceplate
below your eyebrows, it is supposed to be accepted.  Since lots of
people blink when something comes directly at their face, it is
accepted practice to ask a marshall if the tip touched face - so
new fighters may think that they don't have to learn to swing a
good blow if they learn to face thrust.  I've spent many years in
the Middle kingdom, where there is no face thrust, and it does seem
the "average skill level" argument may have some validity.  Of
course, the shields used here average much bigger than those in the
Middle (crown legal in the middle == 26" largest dimension, varies
in Atlantia, last crown was 34" (I think - maybe 32)) which has a
serious effect on the usefulness of some kinds of blows and on the
thrusting tip.  (As a side note, the next crown has no limit on
the size of shields, but they must weigh 2 1/2 pounds per square
foot -- figure it out - a steel round at 24" just barely makes the
minimum -- lots of people should be in for a surprise :-) !!)

Helmet padding:  I use duct tape rolled into a loop on the padding
instead of glue -- lots easier to remove if I want to for either
helmet repair or padding replacement.  Don't forget that a legal
option is a suspension harness mounted in the helm, rather than
padding (at least by society standards its legal, possibly not in
some kingdoms).  The people I know that use harness say that it
lets them breathe and hear much better, and is lots cooler too.  The
disadvantage is that the helmet may tend to ring a lot without padding
to deaden it.

