Unto the gentil readers of the rialto, Li Kung Lo once again sends greetings!
It has been a long time since I have gotten my digests (thanks Jane and
Justin), and it seems you have been having this great, although becoming
repetitious, discussion of pagan religion, and the treatment of religion in
the SCA. Well, before this whole thing is over, I'd like a chance to put in my
two cent's worth.
        Thanks to Awilda Halfdane (blessed be, sister), Cher de Bellevue,
Samuel Basset, Meow, and of course, William de Corbie for their thought
provoking comments. While I cannot truly shed light on this, I can share my
own experiences, as both an ethnologist/archeologist (I gave up that line to
go into nursing), and as a pagan raised to traditional craft initiation.
        Milord de Corbie, I take issue with your version of religious history,
and I am disappointed by your narrow view of religious persecution. For a
discussion of the relationship between Christian and Pagan religions during
the middle ages, try *The Spiral Dance*, *The White Goddess*, *Drawing Down
the Moon*, *The Women's Encyclopedia of Myths and Goddesses*, and other
relevent works. 
        Your statement that there are observed regularities in social change
(paraphrase- It conflicts with what we know about social change...) is mostly
mistaken. We have studied social process for about 100 years in an ever more
rigorous manner, and we know almost nothing about it. Such historical
phenomenon as the vowel shift in the English language elude our explanation
completely. By prior "laws" of lexicostatistics (a branch of linguistic
anthropology dealing with statistical analysis of language change over time)
the English vowel shift should have taken 600-1000 years (actually, it was
about 80).
        Moreover, pagan religion is not organized along the lines of most
modern religions, and therefore does not change in the same way. Oral
traditions are not the same as written traditions, and bronze age politics
aren't corporate. The idea that modern Norse paganism can be compared to
"known facts" about ancient Norse religion assumes that their was a "standard"
set of religious beliefs and practices to be referred to, like a Christian
creed and liturgy, but this is not true. Traditional religion far more likely
varied between regions, households, sexes, social classes, and family groups
as much as it does with the practices of modern Norse Pagans.
        I will grant as a given that most modern Norse Pagans have drawn the
majority, if not all, of their beliefs and practices from written sources
describing ancient Norse customs. However, the idea of a secret religious
practice is *not* ridiculous. By conservative estimates, between the years of
1450 and 1670, 5-7 million people were tortured and put to death as witches by
the Christian churches of Europe and their secular representatives, the
majority of them women. (see *Gyn-Ecology* by Mary Daly on the burning times)
During this dark period, many of the local pagan practices which had survived
the early Christianization of Europe went out of sight, along with midwifery,
hypnosis/suggestion, herbalism, animal training techniques, native
toxicology/pharmacology, and a host of other skills which comprised the core
of the craft.
        When I was 8 years old, and I went to public school, the teacher asked
me, "What religion are you, Richie?", and I answered, "none", because I knew
it was better than facing the ridicule, laughter, and possible injury that
would result from telling the truth. Today in 1989, I work in a Seventh-Day
Adventist Hospital, and refuse to work on any of the sabbats. I wear my
pentagram proudly, and teach about paganism to any *interested* party. 
        Milord de Corbie, the violation of someone's civil rights, regardless
of the popularity or lack therof of their beliefs, is never deserved, and to
decry the crimes of those who would deny those rights (even Jews attacking
Naziists) is not "whining". 
        Our religion, or "craft", because religion is only a component of it,
is an ancient one, an oral tradition practiced under the stars, and in the oak
groves of ancient forests. It usually has no houses of worship, no corporate
entity, no real estate, no taxes, no tithes, no creed, and no visibility. It
is practiced by small groups of people, whose beliefs vary widely from group
to group, as do our rituals. Mostly we have in common only the idea that
there is a female quality (a goddess) in creation, distinct and separate from
the male quality. Some of us worship the two, some just the goddess, and
some many gods. Many of us can recite the act of contrition as readily as a
fervent Catholic, and many, like myself, were born to it, and are the
recipients of an oral tradition whose age even we cannot guess.
        The important thing here is what relevence all this has to the SCA,
and hence this forum. It is my belief that you have beaten this dead horse
