Well, I've been quiet for a while and this lets me post without getting too
viament.

For a long time, I had no use for thrusting tips. Not for the reasons stated
in Mike's area, but simply because I hadn't figured out how to use them. If
I have to think to do a technique, I'll almost never use it. I still don't
have them on my broad swords. I don't feel they would be effective against
the "convention*" body armour, the East has only just allowed (limited) face
thrusting, and, as I said above, I am not practiced in the moves, so I
wouldn't use them most of the time anyway. (Just what I need, another way
for my weapons/armour to fail! ;-)

That being said, on a polearm, bastard sword, or great-sword thrusting tips
are... well... great! They offer a whole new dimension in ways to "reach
out and touch someone!":-) With a six foot weapon I can hit a target at
8.5+ feet on a lunge, or 7.5 without full extention but easily followed by
a quick close to toe to toe. Never fails to amaze your friends ;-).

As to the objections of the group you are in now (Where is that, BTW?),
it sounds like they would have a problem anyway. You have to know where the
rattan ends to hit someone, and if the thrusting tip is "robbing" them, they
need to rethink range. As I've previously opined, the tip is not what you
want to strike with anyway.  Even though it is the fastest moving part of
the weapon, it is the most easily deflected, and is not likely to defeat
"convention" armour and incapacitate your opponent.

If you live in one of those areas where folks stand at extreme range behind
huge shields and only throw tip shots (e.g. the East), I can see their
objection. I've been to too many tournements where this was standard. It
gets to sounding like a diet beer commercial about waiters with all the
"lights", "lows", and "tips" being called ;-). Besides, it's hard to get
around those shields with a bastard sword;-)(Ah ha! the real reason! ;-).
Although I have had to inform opponents that they could get up if they
wanted to, "It was only a tip." ;-)

		Bart the Bewildered
		(Don't ask me about Crown, I'm just the autocrat!)
		Barony of Carillion, East
		(mka Paul Kay, NJ, USA)

* By "convention" I mean "That defined as the standard of armour published
  in the conventions of combat for the society"; heavy mail, cuire-boilee
  arms and legs, open face helm, as I recall.

