Good Baroness, and people of the Rialto --
 
In reading Enid's posting several similar but different situations
came to mind, and one of the most common is that of the fighter who
is extraordinarily good, has talent in several other areas, and
whose attitudes about chivalry and, particularly, knighthood, stink.
I've known several of these folk, and it occurs to me that the
Chivalry are particularly good at finding someone who can go up to
this person and say "Listen, we think you're a great fighter, and a
talented burble-maker, but if your attitude doesn't improve you're
going to find yourself never getting any further in the SCA." Now,
perhaps this capitalizes on the person's lust for "danglies", but it
seems to me that in some cases, at least, the possible recipient
isn't aware of the problems that he/she is causing, and some frank
assessment by a trusted friend is in order.
 
It's been said in my hearing that Pelicans don't have to be nice/
chivalrous/ pleasant/ or courteous, they just have to get lots of
work done. I, personally, think this is a wrong idea, and we should
be encouraging the appropriate sorts of behaviors at all levels. On
the one hand, I agree with the folks who say that we should reward
good behavior and not negatively reinforce the bad, but sometimes
you find folks who are so oblivious to life around them that you
have to speak bluntly.
 
Remember the old saying about mules and 2x4's -- 
    "first, you have to get his attention...."
 
Regards,
