From: "]ke Eldberg" <CONS.ELF@AIDA.CSD.UU.SE>
Subject: Witches & flames
Message-ID: <890323182326.8.CONS.ELF@AIDA.CSD.UU.SE>

This is in the nature of a reply to Lord Yaakov Hamizrachiy.

I feel that you are right in your observations about the differences between
natural sciences and humanist scholarship. I would like to add a bit, though:

In the natural sciences, most things are provable by experiment or logics.
This means that it is very difficult to lie and have people believe you.
Also, the knowledge we get through natural sciences seldom touches directly
onout values, morals, beliefs or ways of life. Therefore, there is very 
little incentive to speculate or lie, and you can normally trust what you
read if the author is a respected scientist.

The findings of humanist sciences affect our feelings much more. Since we
seldom get a single, all-covering explanation of any phenomenon in these
sciences, there is always room for different viewpoints and it's wasy to
bend the truth if one wants to. There is also a large incentive for us to
involve our personal opinions in these matters.

This is why the literature on humanist sciences is full of prejudice, wild
guesses, wishful thinking, attempts to exaggerate one explanation while 
omitting another, and even outright lies. And even when the books tell the
truth, we who read them sometimes do not read what is there, but interpret
it according to our own prejudice. The result is that in order to find the
truth, it's not enough to read one or two books by respectable scholars.
You must read a lot of books, you must be critical of your sources, you
must constantly question everything because there are few absolutes. This
is why it takes a lot of time and experience to learn these sciences. There
are no "wiz kids" in history or theology.

Now, on to my recent flame. I regret that posting because it was too harshly
phrased and not very courteous. But I stand by the factual contents as such.

> You council that anyone who does not bow to the dictates of society
> is a fool worthy of chastisement.

NO! I DO NOT!

First, I did not say that we should bow to anything. On thy contrary, we
should try to educate everybody into a greater tolerance. But if you know
that there is a widespread prejudice against your group, and you openly
declare yourself to belong to that group, you *should be aware of* that
you are asking for trouble. Go out and make yourself a martyr if you want,
but don't whine about it, and don't act as if it came as a surprise to you.

Second there is a difference between witches and other minorities:

The bigotry and prejudice that prompts some people to persecute religious
or ethnic minorities usually has its roots in fear of a group of people
with different habits, different looks, different culture &c. It is mostly
a gut feeling that "they" are a threat to "us". This is then boosted by
the fellowship you can develop amongst your own group by uniting aginst
the others.

But most people don't even think of witches as a religious or ethnic minority.
Most people are not aware that there exists a group of people who call
themselves witches and that this means they practise a religion.

In our language, a witch is an evil creature out of the fairy tales. Together
with trolls, demons, vampires, werewolves and a whole bunch of other fantasy
creatures, they are the vehicles of evil in the old sagas. In history, witches
are women who were accused of being identical in behavior to the witches in
literature, i.e. satanists, i.e. consciously evil and hostile to people.

Imagine somebody living in a Jewish neighborhood, who wears a swastika and
claims to be a nazist. Guess what the Jews will do? And then the nazist
whines "But don't you know that there are *good* nazis, too?" This is virtually
the same thing as claiming to be a witch in our society. That witches are
evil is part of the *definition* in all western languages, as far as I know.
If you talk about "good" witches, people won't understand what you mean. You
might as well talk about good rapists, good nazis, good murderers or good
devils.

We may want to change this. We may want to change the definition of the word
"witch" in the common consciousness, But as it is today, we can hardly blame
those who react negatively against someone who claims to be a witch. They
are not necessarily bigots, they just happen to speal a language where "witch"
in a well-known word meaning "evil woman". It's not *their* obligation to
know that there is a small group of intellectuals somewhere who have re-defined
that word. It is up to us to tell them.

William de Corbie
