Date: 23 Mar 89 17:10:29 GMT
From: haste+@andrew.cmu.edu  (Dani Zweig)
Subject: Re: A Response to M'lord de Corbie
Message-Id: <gY-GI5y00Xo805D19e@andrew.cmu.edu>

SSKATZ@pucc.Princeton.EDU (Seth S. Katz):
>M'lord de Corbie...maintains that there
>are 2 branches of science--natural and humanistic.  To speak
>with authority in either requires many years of training...
>...
>As to the first, as you yourself pointed out, knowledge in these fields
>is much more elastic.  Second, scince the basic tenets of these
>humanist sciences concern all people, and we are familiar with the
>basic concepts involved it takes far less time to appreciate
>humanist science occurances than it does to understand the natural
>science.  Example: I can get an a basic understanding of 1066 in
>an hour, whereas it will take me weeks to understand Orgo.

>Second, unlike in the natural sciences, there is no one right
>answer.  Nor is it always possible to have complete information.
>Therefore, people feel far more justified speculating in the humanist
>sciences.

I have to side with the crows on this one.  We are drifting off the Rialto and
out to sea, so I'll limit the verbiage as much as possible.

a)  The social sciences, like the natural sciences, contain good work and sloppy
work, and the people in the relevant fields generally know which is which.

b)  To the extent that this has been tested it has been repeatedly shown that
people do *not* understand the "basic concepts".

c)  It doesn't take less time to understand, when dealing with the humanistic
sciences.  It just takes less time to *think* you understand.  The understanding
of 1066-and-all-that that you can get in an hour is worth as much as the
understanding of quantum mechanics that you can get in a one-hour popular
science lecture given by Mr. Knowitall or some similar luminary.  It's just
harder to fool yourself when dealing with the natural sciences.

e)  Not having "right answers" and "complete information" is hardly the sole
curse of the humanities.  On the other hand, there are scads and scads of
*wrong* answers.  The study of the humanities is to a large extent devoted to
identifying old mistakes.  What makes sophomoric arguments sophomoric is that
they tend to use as givens arguments which were bandied and rejected years,
decades or centuries ago.

Certainly there are major differences between the natural sciences and the
humanities, but many of these stem from the fact that the natural sciences are,
intrinsically so much easier that it is much easier to detect BS in those fields
and much more difficult to pass such BS as legitimate currency.

