    While this is not an appropriate topic for this newsgroup, I feel
compelled to respond to Don Levey's article.   Even so, I will try to
keep it short.

Don Levey:

> Regarding science, I view it as a way that we humans see the world. We 
> observe a phenomenon, and make up a rule to explain it. The rule proves
> wrong, and we make up another one. In short, science is a set of constraints
> artificially imposed upon nature by man.

    Science is not a "set of constraints artificially imposed on nature
by man".   Science is a series of common sense rules for figuring out complex
natural phenomina.  First you guess.   Then you perform experiments to
try to figure out if your guess is right or wrong.   Then you guess again.
This does not constrain the natural event in the least.

    The use of the word "artificial" is interesting.   What is a 'Set of
constraints "naturally" imposed on nature'?    Most of the words Don uses
are completely devoid of meaning in the context that he puts them.

>                                          There are things which cannot be
> explained by science, and things which are in direct conflict with it.

    There are indeed "things" which cannot be explain by science.   Science
cannot tell what Julius Ceasar has for breakfast on his 17th birthday,
science cannot tell what happened before this universe existed, science
cannot proove one priests spiritual theory over anothers (unless experimental
data suddenly comes available -- such as a heavanly host appearing).

    Science limits itself to things which can be manifestly proven TRUE
or FALSE.   This limits it's scope, but also gives it tremendous power.
It turns out many things can be proven True or False, which once were
the province of chance (attended by much hope, prayer, and ritual).

    This worries some priests.   Once, people went to a Priest when they
were sick.   Now they go to a doctor.   The priest offered hope and prayer.
Now, the doctor can often offer a cure.   Some selfish priests hate the loss
of prestege.   They put their own pride before the health of their people,
and try to "disprove" science.  Usually, they only show their own ignorance.


> For fun, try reconciling the special theory of relativity with quantum
> mechanics. It can't be done. They are both accepted as true, and yet they
> are in direct conflict with each other on several points.

    This is false.  Quantum Mechanics subsumed the General Theory of
Relativity (which subsumed the Special Theory of Relativity).   They
are not in any conflict with one another.

    Furthermore, even where there ARE paradoxes with hypothesis/theories,
this only shows that one or another theory is incorrect on some point.
It does not show that Science itself is incorrect.

