Regarding science, I view it as a way that we humans see the world. We 
observe a phenomenon, and make up a rule to explain it. The rule proves
wrong, and we make up another one. In short, science is a set of constraints
artificially imposed upon nature by man. There are things which cannot be
explained by science, and things which are in direct conflict with it.
For fun, try reconciling the special theory of relativity with quantum
mechanics. It can't be done. They are both accepted as true, and yet they
are in direct conflict with each other on several points. I mention this
only because you mention that the existance of an authentic sect of Norse
religion is scientifically imposible. So is the random coalescance of
molecules to form life, which is why we have God anyway.

Personally, as a clergyperson myself (Cantor in a synogogue (Jewish)), I
have severe problems with ANY religion that claims divine origin and right,
to the exclusion of all others. Judaism does it, so does Christianity (please
forgive my lumping all sects into one category), and so do most other major
religions. From a sociological standpoint, that's how to run a religion.
If you claim that yours is the only "light and path," then people have more
of an incentive to follow you. I don't really care if you worship Ralph, the
sacred Head of Lettuce, but please don't tell me that what I do isn't 
religiously or scientifically correct. How much of religion can stand the
scrutiny of science anyway?

