Subject: Norse Paganism

afreeman writes (memo.102793@lynx.northeastern.edu):

>I recall that at the christianising of the Norse, there had been a book
>published relating the theology being extinguished, The deception of
>Saint something-or-other. Does anyone know if this is available in
>modern english?

I think you have heard a garbled reference to the first part of
Snorri Sturluson's Edda, and yes, it's available in English. But
first, a little background:

Iceland converted to Christianity in 1000 CE, by parliamentary decision
--a pretty unique conversion. People who wished to continue worshipping
the old gods in private could do so--Iceland was, and remains, a
tolerant society--but pagan practices like exposing unwanted babies and
eating horsemeat were banned. So there was a fairly graceful transition
from one faith to the other, and the myths and legends lingered on as
part of the general literary culture.

But by the mid-thirteenth century this old-faith literary background
was being forgotten. This worried Snorri Sturluson, who was a leading
political and literary figure (same thing in Iceland) of the time.
In an effort to preserve what he saw as Iceland's literary heritage,
Snorri wrote a book he called _Edda_--the title may or may not mean
"grandmother", and there's disagreement about what Snorri meant by it.
_Edda_ was divided into three parts: "The Deluding of Gylfi", which 
retells many of the old myths (Gylfi is a king, not a saint); "Poetic
Diction", which gives the necessary background to understand various
literary allusions, telling a fair number of stories in the process;
and "The Enumeration of Meters", which is a poem of 102 stanzas, each
stanza in a different skaldic meter. What is *not* recorded anywhere
in the Edda is *anything* of the theology, doctrine, or religious
practices of the pagan Norse--these were long lost (or thoroughly
secret, if you insist), and Snorri was a good Christian for his time.
Snorri's book, called variously the Prose Edda, the Younger Edda, or
(logically) Snorri's Edda, is available in many English translations;
any good academic library should have a couple (prefer the most
recent if you have a choice). Other works by Snorri include the Heims-
kringla--tales of the Norwegian kings (see the story of Haakon the
Good for a wonderful attempt at compromise between the Christian king
Haakon and the pagan Norwegians)--and (almost certainly) Egil's Saga.

The reason I give so much background (besides my natural inclination)
is because all this touches on two other things I want to bring up:

1) In all the discussion I have been reading here about revived and/or
preserved Norse paganism, no one seems to have mentioned that Asatro,
the worship of the AEsir, is a state religion in modern Iceland along
with Lutheranism. They are a minority religion, true, but they are
certainly not persecuted (neither do they go about baiting Christians).
They are not skinheads or neo-Nazis but rather, by and large, they seem
pretty funky. In all the interviews with their clergy that I have read
(like two, I think, so I could be wrong on this), they make no claim
to a continuous, unbroken, underground tradition surviving intact since
1000; instead they claim to be a reconstructed, revived religion. I'm
not even going to *begin* to judge how scholarly or accurate they may
be in this, but there you are: a state-sanctioned Western European
revived pagan church.

2) (for my own research) There are plenty of stories of individual
Christians in Iceland before the year 1000; but can someone
out there direct me to *any* figure in the saga literature who stayed
pagan after the conversion?

If you've read all the way this far, I recommend to you Chapter 103
of Njals Saga for a *controlled* experiment to test the relative worth
of Christianity and paganism, I apologize for taking up your time, and
I thank you.

