Subject: Ice Dragon Anecdotes

Ice Dragon is a Rhydderich Hael (Buffalo) baronial event that got out of hand.
This year it was limited to 600 people -- 320 onboard and 280 offboard.  There's
a fencing tourney, but its main features are its rattan tourney and its arts and
science competition -- each with over a hundred entries.  So much for background.

1.  Most of the peformance entries in the A&S competition came from the BMDL
(Barony Marche of the Debatable Lands/Pittsburgh).  This was apparently
perceived as being due in large part to the encouragement of Remus Fletcher, so
he was drafted as one of the judges.  Unfortunately (from the A&S standpoint)
Remus is a good fighter, and they were worried that he wouldn't be eliminated
from the tourney in time for the judging.  So the A&S office put a price on his
head:  One pound of Hershey's kisses, payable to the fighter who eliminated
Remus Fletcher before 1:30 PM.  (Duke Visivald collected.)

2.  Partway through the evening an extremely irate autocrat announced that there
was a crying child who had been left in the children's room *unattended*.  Five
people got up and left the feast hall.

3.  One of the performance entries (instrumental, solo) was a very poorly
documented piece of Viking music, entered by the first person ever to submit
entries in all twelve major categories of the Arts Pentathlon.  I was later
told, by someone who recognized the music, that the reason it was so poorly
documented was that it was, in reality, the music for "Bend Over Greek Sailor".
(A rowing song, of course.)

4.  It was announced at the Court that the western part of the East Kingdom had
voted to become a principality.  The poll also resulted in opting for the name
"Principality of the Lakes" (I'll skip the editorial comments) and a device
(someone want to put it in heraldese?) that looks more or less like a white
snowflake on a red background.  We were *not* *officially* told what the
principality would contain.

