Subject: Paganism & religion in Sweden

Just to explain how really different the US and Sweden may be, (to both swedes
and americans), I'd like to post a few observations on paganism and religion
in Sweden. First of all, I should probably state Im an agnostic myself 
(mundanely), of the rather sceptic, non-believing kind. For all Ive read
it seems that noone of this (non)conviction has put forward any comments.

The most important fact of religion in Sweden is the existence of a State 
church. This church has been Lutheran since the reformation enforced
by king Gustav Vasa in 16th century. The majority  of the swedish people are
still members of this church, altough many of them for reasons of tradition
or disinterest only. (Your made a member when born and have to actively leave
the organisation not to be). In my very nonreligious family my parents
used go to church a couple of times around christmas, more to achieve
"christmas mood" than for religious needs, I think.

Other churches include those of various immigrant communities (including
mainstream catholics) and the kind churches known in Sweden as "free churches",
ie Baptists, Methodists, Salvation Army and so forth. There are also rather
active communties of mormons and witnesses. Mosaic congregations  have
existed for at least a couple of hundred years.

Pagans in Sweden come in two varieties: Nordic and others. While the "Others" 
resemble the descriptions of US pagans given by various posters, the "nordic"
belivers have a large percentage right-wing, skinhead, anti-immigrant and even
anti-american type of people that make them very hard to take seriously as a 
religious group.

