Sam'l Basset is right that "science" means a different thing in Europe than
it does in the USA. Here in Europe, it means any kind of knowledge which
has been proved with rationally acceptable methods. We make a difference
between "natural sciences" which are math, physics, chemistry &c, and 
"humanist sciences" which are history, religion, literature &c.

The humanist sciences are less absolute than the natural ones. For instance,
we cannot know for certain that Julius Caesar has existed, since he is not
available for examination. Almost all humanistic knowledge is non-provable
in the natural-science-sense of the word. Further, humanist knowledge 
touches directly on the opinions and thoughts of the people involved. It is
difficult to be objective even if you desire objectivity, which not all
"scientists" do. Many historians set out with the avowed purpose of proving
a point, e.g. marxist historians whi are out to reveal the class struggle
in everything they see.

The subjects which "humanist sciences" research are often terribly compli-
cated, and there is usually a wide choice of different ways to approach them.
All too often, we choose our method not according to what we want to really 
want to know, but according to which tools that are available, or (worse)
according to what suits our personal opinions and biases.

When you read a book on history, religion or any other "humanist science",
it takes *a lot* of knowledge on your part, for you to be able to detect
such errors. I'm not saying that true knowledge is impossible here. We may
not always be able to present "hard fact" types of data of the sort which
is usually available in the natural sciences. But there is still a vast
difference between scientifically established facts on the one hand, and
subjective opinions/wishful thinking/conjecture on the other, in humanistic
sciences.

I would like to administer an admonition to all who take part in the discus-
sion on religion. Call me a "wise guy" or a "know-it-all" if that makes you
happier. I know this sounds really stuffy and up-tight, especially with my
less-than-perfect command of English style of language. But here it is.

You can't just read a couple of books and then throw yourself into a debate
thinking that you *know* what you are talking about. I have seen postings
on religion here which indicate a fundamental ignorance combined with an
absolute conviction on the part of the poster that he/she is well-informed.

Science is like a mountain. To get to the top, you must climb from the bottom.
If you take a shortcut (a helicopter that puts you on the top), you will see
the top but you won't know what's under you. You will make gross mistakes.
And up there, it's very difficult for those who *really* know these things
to explain them to you - because you lack the basics. GO TO "START" WITHOUT
COLLECTING THE NOBEL PRIZE.

Consider the natural sciences: an intelligent but uneducated person cannot
immediately understand a doctor's thesis in molecular physics. Perhaps a
good teacher can explain what it's about. But to truly understand such a
thing, you need 20 years of education and practise. You must know mathematics.
You must be familiar with scientific procedures, laboratory methods, logics,
philosophy, and the current state of research. Without these, you will not
be able to understand how all these things lead up to a certain piece of
truth.

In natural sciences, people tend to accept "scientific" facts which they
lack the education to truly understand. We believe what the scientists tell
us about physics, math, chemistry. But in humanist sciences, everybody is
suddenly an expert, and the words of a scientist who has worked with these
things for 20 years and *knows* are questioned by many people who have
only read an article in Reader's Digest. 

My admonition is: don't make cocksure statements if you haven't climbed the
mountain. Don't trust the helicopters (popular books and articles). Be
careful lest you spread untruth. One example is the discussion about wether
the Church cared what the peasants believed in. The answer, irritatingly, is
both yes and no. 

William de Corbie
