Subject: religion for peasants/witchcraft

Greetings gentles from Juliana of Felding, Carolingia, East

As I am currently taking a history class on religion and witchcraft in the 
Middle Ages and Renaissance, I feel that I must address some of the points on
peasants, heresy, religion, and witchcraft in our time period.  Unfortunately, 
much of the scholarship until recently had heavy biases.  A good example of 
this phenomenon is Steven Ozment who was a Lutheran minister before teaching 
religious history at Harvard.  Thus, one must take the scholarship, especially 
that of 20+ years ago with a very large grain of salt.

To a very large extent peasants in the Middle Ages were allowed to believe 
what they wanted as long as they paid their tithes, went to confession and 
received communion once a year.  Often the village priest was not much more 
educated than the rest of the populus with the exception of knowing enough 
Latin to be able to say the mass (which often he did not completely understand).
Keith Thomas in his _Religion and the Decline of Magic_ cites many examples of 
practices that the Church put up with that definitely had pagan overtones.  
Ecclesiastical debates centered around universities and papers written in Latin,
therefore only a small segment of the population truly understood Catholic 
doctrine in all its complexity.  In fact, many of Luther's concerns had been 
discussed for years in the universities, with little repercussions on the 
author or the populus, witness John Wyclif in England.  Reformers such as 
Wyclif, Erasmus, and Thomas More challenged the excesses of the Church, in 
relation to mispent money and clerical abuses, such that many comtemporary 
scholars believe that the Church in the late 15th century was "more pure" than 
in the past.  Thus, Luther's popularity was intricately tied to the phenomenon 
of the printing press which allowed his translated message to be seen and 
understood by the merchant and artisan classes.  Heretical movements 
before 1520 were often allowed to exist for a while before the church did 
anything because they often died out on their own.  Often, secular authorities 
felt more threatened by the movements because economic concerns were often on 
the heretics agenda.  For example, Jan Hus of Bohemia was burned by Emperor
Sigismund in the 14th cent., not by the Church.  The Church only became severly 
repressive after the advent of Luther because of the can of worms (versus the 
diet of worms) that was opened as people began to read the vernacular Bible 
and come up with their own ideas, in conflict with Catholic doctrine.  

Now, as to witchcraft, that was a phenomenon strongly attached to the 
Reformation, Counter-Reformation, and misogynist attitudes of the 16th and 17th 
centuries.  In the Middle Ages, convents flourished as a place for women who 
"didn't fit" to go.  Admittedly, they was predominantly for upper-class women, 
but they also provided charity for widows and unmarried young women of lower 
classes.
With Luther's emphasis on salvation "by faith alone" and religious experience in
marriage, good works like charity declined as well as convent populations. In 
England many convents were closed due to smaller populations and for increased 
revenue for the monarchy.  To be fair to Luther, he stated that while man could 
be saved only through faith, good works would follow since he would be a "good 
man" and do them naturally.  Therefore, there were fewer acceptable places for 
women to go who "didn't fit" and charity for widows and unmarried women fell 
off dramatically.  Scapegoatism ensued because women became more of a "burden 
to society".  Witchcraft trials often started with widows being the first 
accused.  Inquisitors often employed torture to "discover" who else in the 
village associated with the "witch", leading to false accusations.  Often the 
trial stopped in an area when wives of top officials were implicated, leading 
to questions of veracity of the trial.

I will be able to offer more on the question of witchcraft as my class 
continues this semester.  In the hopes of adding accurate historical evidence 
to the debate on religious issues, I am

