Date:     Sun, 19 Mar 89 17:06 EDT
From:     <CRF%IFASGNV.BITNET@mitvma.mit.edu>
Subject:  Children

Greetings!

I have just finished reading Mistress Siobhan's recent postings on the subject
of children.  I heartily support everything she says.  I should now like to
address the problem of dealing with the parents of children who mis-behave,
and would like it noted that I literally grew up behind a lunch counter on
Long Island (my parents owned a luncheonette in Great Neck for more than 20
years...).  So, I've dealt with these problems in a mundane capacity as well
as in a Society capacity.

*The* big problem with dealing with this sort of parent is their tendency to
refuse to believe that *their* child is a problem.  I've always found that
parents of erring children, when spoken to, react in one of two ways:  either
they grab their kids by the ear and haul them off to be reprimanded; or they
take *great* umbrage and cause a huge scene, or ignore the situation
completely!

Either of these latter scenaria are difficult to deal with.  I can't say I
honestly blame seneschals (etc.) from not wishing to deal with such
situations.  People will accept reprimands about their own behavior
gracefully, yet perceive complaints about their childrens' behavior (however
well justified) as a personal attack.

Let me relate an anecdote from my days as a child short-order cook:  our
luncheonette was located but a mile from the police station.  When my parents
would catch a child shoplifting, they took the kid to the back of the store
where the 'phones were.  My father would then hand the kid a dime and say,
"You have a choice:  either *you* call your parents and tell them what you
did, and tell them to come get you; or *I* call the cops, the cops take you to
the police station, and *they* call your parents and tell them what you've
done."  The kids *invariably* called their parents.

Well, one evening my mother caught a young boy stealing candy.  The familiar
ritual was performed, ending with the boy calling his parents.  The boy's
father soon appeared.  He grabbed the boy by the collar and said, "Get on your
bike, get your ass home, and you *will* be in your room when I get there!"
The father then thanked my parents, saying that there had been problems with
the boy, and left.

BUT:  the next day, the boy's mother came in.  A monumental scene between this
woman and my mother ensued, which consisted mainly of this woman following my
mother around screaming that *her* son would *never* do such a thing; how
*dare* my parents make these accusations!  The woman only left when my mother
picked up the 'phone to report her for trespassing!

The memory of this incident has always remained vivid, and has always summed
up for me the negative side of the very issue we're discussing.  The only ways
I've ever known to deal with parents who refuse to accept responsibility for
their kids' behavior are as follows (and are partially dependent on the age of
the child(ren) involved):  if you are the autocrat, or whatever, put your foot
down firmly but politely and *don't* budge it; or, put first the child and
then the parents in a position where they *must* acknowledge the problem.
This goes whether you wish merely to talk to the parents, or to eject the
family from the site (the possibility of which must be accepted and faced up
to).  In effect, this is the approach my parents always used so well, and I
admit it.

And, it *does* work in a Society context.  When once I caught some kids *way*
out of line, I spoke to them severely (they all knew me, and I them), then
sent them to their parents with instructions to tell their parents what they
had done.  I made it clear that I'd be checking up on things.  Lo and behold,
they all did as they were told!  The lot of them later appeared on my doorstep
(tentstep?), led by one of the mothers, and apologized!

I realize that some of what I've written may seem harsh.  But I agree with
Mistrss Siobhan:  it is unfair for the group at large to be expected to put up
with such disruptions, and by so few.  That the SCA is a family group does
*not* excuse parents from their responsibilities!

Thank you for reading this.


