A few words about whether the Church 'cared' about the spirituality
of the peasants.
Such questions are real sticky, and almost impossible to prove.
Of course, the Archbishop of Canterbary (sp?) is going to spend
a lot of time with the King of England, both from a church poltical
point of view and because the Archbishop is The King's personal
confessor, and needs to minister to his personal spiritual needs.
History (and historians) tend to focus on the 'big guns' like
kings, bishops and nobles, while leaving the 'small fry' parish
priests and peasants out of the limelight.  But the Catholic (meaning
all encompasing) church did not forget the either the town man-in-the
street or the serf-in-the-manure.  Criticism of the Church came latter
in the period, and led to the formation within the Church of movements
to 'reach out to the common people'. This was the original purpose behind
the Fransicans and Dominicans.  Always, however, the temptation lay for
the Church heirarchy to concern itself with politics, wealth, and the local
big-guns.  In short- statements such as the church did (not) care at all
about the peasants are subjective and are not constant through history.
