 Ellisif Flakkingskvinne writes:
 
> [some description of disruptive kids deleted -- we all know what
> it's like!]
>
>  Yet all of these have happened from time to time because the
> parents haven't accepted the extra *responsibility* that goes with bringing k
> ids to events.  I don't think the burden of taking care of the kids should
> fall on everyone else who shows up at an event.
>
> Most parents aren't this way, of course, and it would be a shame to punish
> all for the sake of a few.  (Especially since, when parents cooperate, the
> SCA can be a major positive influence on a child's socialization.)  But for
> those who are this rude and/or negligent, what is the proper way to handle the
> situation (assuming it's a chronic problem)?  Should the autocrat, seneschal,
> or officers ask the parents to take the offending kids home?  (Probably a bad
> precedent -- "You annoy me, so you'll have to leave."  And how would you
> modify your answer if the offending parent was the autocrat, seneschal, other
> officer, or from out of town?)  Should all kids be banned, to avoid singling
> people out?  (Bad move, in my opinion.)  Should we all bite the bullet and
> live with it, as the society slowly generates more and more children?  (And
> the potential problems get worse and worse....)  All of these options have
> big problems.  Any suggestions?
 
What a dilemma! Good question, milady!
 
I once had a very heated argument about this very topic with the
seneschal of a nearby group. It seems that they had, at the time,
only one couple with children, and those children were (and still
are, some 5 years later, sigh) very un-managed and disruptive. At
the time, this group had a habit of meeting at people's houses over
the summer, when the college was closed, and they had some people
who did not want to allow children in their houses at all, much less
these 3 disruptive brats. So they made a ruling that if the "host"
(and i use the word loosely) wished, people with children could be
banned from the public meeting for that particular meeting, or made
to stay outdoors while the rest of the business meeting went on
inside. They posted their monthly schedule in advance of the
meeting, and some of those meetings were labelled "no children".
 
Now, as a parent who sometimes visited this group, with my child, I
was very annoyed about this, especially when the seneschal admitted
to me that the real problem wasn't children in general, but these
particular children. I don't understand (and probably never will)
why people don't face up to problems and deal with them on a
personal level rather than making them bigger by dealing with them
bureaucratically. I urged the seneschal to talk to these parents,
let them know that their children were being pests, and ask them to
please take them in hand. Such behavior would not be tolerated in
adults -- in our local group we have had adults who were disruptive
and obnoxious, and no one waited around to tell these folks that
their behavior needed to be modified. But this seneschal felt that
he had no right to ask these parents to control their kids. [Anyone
have any hints about that? Are we as parents so grumpy over the
subject of our kids that no one wants to approach us about their
behavior?]
 
[As a side-side note, our local barony has a policy that a meeting
cannot be held in any location which is not open to all members of
the group. Therefore, we can't schedule meetings in a University
room which isn't open to, say, men, or other such restrictions. It's
also true that we've used this to squelch factionalism -- when we
had a nasty schism, once, we had people who wouldn't let other
people on their property. No meetings could be held at that house
while that policy was in effect. It's been good for us.]
 
As an autocrat or other officer at an event, I've never hesitated to
let a parent know when his or her kid was doing something stupid,
disruptive, or dangerous. When I caught a group of kids "skiing"
down a stack of tables in the back of our feast hall when the hall
was closed (the kids were about 8) I collared the rascals and
marched them back out to general area, and didn't release them to
their parents until I let the parents know what was going on. I also
told the parents as kindly and firmly as I could that I was busy
cooking, and that we did not have daycare at this event, and that
the responsibility of looking after their children belonged to them.
 
I may be more aggressive about this because I am a mother, and I
know that if my kid was doing something disruptive I would want to
know about it!
 
I think (take a deep breath and be brave here) that if a child
continually disrupts an event, or is crying in court perpetually, or
is repeatedly and generally obnoxious, then the seneschal of the
group has every right to ask the parent to remove the child. It
doesn't have to be a public banning -- but a quiet word, and an
offer to help with the parent's stuff, is probably appropriate.
We've removed adults for drunkenness -- quietly, with a knight
escorting a rowdy gentle out and helping them find someone to drive
them home -- and other obnoxious behavior. Why can't we do the same
for children?
 
Thank you for your patience with my ramblings.
 
     Siobhan
 
