Date: Fri, 17 Mar 89 09:33 EST
From: SHAVA@ISIS.MIT.EDU
Subject: sincere pagans

I don't have the text anymore, but some gentle in an earlier missive commented
that for a pagan to be a "sham" protestant (for instance), and not an out-of-
the-closet pagan, they must be insincere.

I am a Unitarian Universalist and Jewish by upbringing, a pagan by practice. 
I am on the national committee in the Unitarian Universalist Assn for pagan 
stuff (CUUPS), and a fairly well out of the closet pagan.  However, I attend
church in the UU community here, and see no contradiction between being an
active pagan and an active UU--nor with being an active buddhist or an active
creation-spirituality-catholic or a number of other things.

BUT, when I was living in a pagan (and mostly SCA) household a few years back,
when Ari and Nicholai (for those of you in carolingia) were getting married,
we decided to have a pre-wedding feast/picnic.  For purposes of this, I 
secured a kid (i.e. young goat) to roast with apples and onions and eggs for
the feast.  Since I went to visit friends on a farm several hours away to
procure this, I didn't get home until midnight.

I had the kid, field-dressed, in a black garbage bag.  I very quietly (since
I wanted it to be a surprise) took it into the kitchen to skin and finish
cleaning it.  When I started to skin it, it occurred to me that tanning a
kidskin would be a very sentimental gift for Ari & Nicholai.  Since I learned
how to tan hides growing up in Vermont, I decided to do this.  

I did a skinning job a taxidermist would have been proud of. (apologies to 
the vegetarian or squeamish gentles out there).  It took me a few hours.  To
keep myself awake (I'd just driven three hours by myself after a full day
in the country...) I sang to myself, moved briskly when I wasn't hunkered
down, and did the usual silly stuff you do when you're dead tired and trying
to keep yourself amused.

Now, we lived in a fairly homogenous Italian Catholic lower middle class 
neighborhood in a not-quite-suburb of Boston.  And it happened that our 
neighbor's kitchen window looked into ours.  And it happened that I was 
protecting my clothing from the mess of the carcass and the tanning bath
by not wearing it.  

The next thing we knew the neighborhood was abuzz that we were: satanists;
sacrificing animals in the house; holding strange rituals and sabbats (after
all they could hear odd music at strange hours...Moussorgsky, probably...:-);
and the board of health came in to shut down the house and evict us.  The
board of health, by the way, can ALWAYS find a reason to shut down a resi-
dency if they think they have enough reason.  Their reasons for us included
that we were breeding animals in the house (we had a cage of rats which 
included babies), that we had the wrong mix of male & female unrelated
folk living in the house (massachusetts 1800's cohabitation laws), and that
there was asbestos in the basement (which was, honestly, nice to know about).

I've never made a lot of noise in general about being pagan.  Most people 
don't cry their religion from the rooftops.  But this incident made me very
aware that scared, uneducated people do scary, ignorant things that can 
*hurt* you.

Ergo, I am very sincere.  I attend a (at least historically) protestant 
church, because I like the philosophy, the social context, and the people.
But I don't put bumper stickers on my car that say "{pentacle} clergy {pent-
acle}" any more than I would put up a bumpersticker that says "Jesus was
a good jewish boy who had trouble with the law."  Religion requires context
to be un-offensive, and offending people is not only rude but can be 
dangerous.

					Thanking the gods for 
					the company of tolerant souls,
						Shava Nerad


