	I would be willing to bet that these lists were from the time of the
"Malleus Maleficarum" (Latin for "Hammer of Witches") done by a couple of
really kinky Dominicans in the 1500s.  Most of the witch-burning in the Middle
Ages was pretty late, and extended into the modern, "post-Society" era -- the
1690s in America.
	Early in our period (1000s, if I remember correctly) a pope issued and
Encyclical explicitly condemning the belief in witches, goddesses, etc., as
being both heretical and nonsense.  It was only in the latter times, when the
Church was facing competition with Protestantism that witch-hunting became a
sport.  Before that time, it was a private enterprise, and not very prominent.

	Virtually all European nobility descends from one or another bunch of
pretty grungy characters who conquered the various countries -- the were the
horsey equivalent of today's Hell's Angels (or maybe vice-versa -- will the
H.A.s' descendants look down their noses at ours ???  :-)
	Most of them went through, raping, looting, sacking, and pillaging,
but some of them settled down --some because they liked the look of the place,
some because there was a good (or very bad) reason they couldn't go home, and
some, doubtless, because it seemed like the thing to do at the time.
	After a certain amount of time, the local King would get Christianized
(Clovis and the Franks, Aethel{somethingorother} in England, etc.), and would
then insist that the larger nobles do the same -- Christianity brought trade
with the richer areas.  If any of the nobles _wouldn't_ convert -- well, that
was as good an excuse as any to hit 'em over the head and appropriate their
lands and treasure.
	As for the peasants -- they got pretty short shrift.  Just think about the
general attitude of your local ("outlaw") motorcycle club towards "citizens",
and you'll get the general idea.  The Church baptized everybody, and paid
attention tothe people with "power" -- however that was defined.  The "power
elite" were trusted to handle everybody else.
	As late as the 1950s, the Roman Church's official attitude towards its
parishioners in the USA was: "Pray, pay, and obey -- or else goto Hell."  That
is still the attitude of the Curia in Rome, and I can't see that it was much
different any earlier.  (Even the pray was pretty much optional, as long as
they paid and obeyed -- considering that most bishops were nobles, this pretty
much reflects the attitudes of European society of the time . . .).
