Greetings!

Before addressing those topics I have in mind for this posting, I wish to
offer kudos unto Sam'l de Basset, William de Corbie, and many others for
their intelligent and informative commentaries on the religion topic.  And,
it's *so* nice that everyone's being civilized, instead of flaming each other!

GAMES:  my Barony, An Crosaire, originated a game called "Boppe ye
Hedgepigge".  To play, all participants stand in a circle and bat around a
small stuffed hedgehog.  This is done amidst much conversation, with *large*
dollops of silliness added!  (Don't knock it; it's proven to be an excellent
means of getting newcomers involved, and for getting to know one another!)

Another activity, which like the one above would be good for kids, are "Hobbye
Tourneys."  Participants enter the "lists" astride hobby-horses, or home-made
"hobby-beasties" of any sort.  They "tilt" at each other wearing cardboard
helms, and bearing cardboard heaters and well-padded boffle lances.  Again,
much silliness is called for.

RE:  PEASANT ACTIVITIES AND SOURCES THEREUPON:  the book Sam'l de Basset has
in mind should be Barbara Tuchman's _A_Distant_Mirror_.  Other books on the
"life cycle" of the peasantry are around, such as _Lost_Country_Life_ (I forget
the authors' names).  I couldn't say offhand which of these documents the
activities which have been indirectly referred to (such as copulating in the
sown fields to insure a good harvest), but I *do* know the documentation is
out there.

MY MOST MAGICAL MOMENT IN THE SCA:  was, I think, during the feast Sat. night
of the first Trimaris Principality Coronation.  My Barony and 2 other groups
co-autocratted, because Trimaris was so proud to be going Principality at last
that *everyone* wanted to pull out all the stops, and thoroughly gild the
lily!  So everyone was looking their best in all respects.  Then, once the
serving was under way, the lights were turned off.  For once, there was ample
candlelight available (the autocrats supplemented what the populace had
brought).  Nothing mundane was visible on the tables.  Suddenly, it all came
together; it was one of those moments when it all becomes real, and it is the
mundane world that seem to be the dream...


