From: "]ke Eldberg" <CONS.ELF@AIDA.CSD.UU.SE>
Subject: More refutatio
Message-ID: <890316014227.16.CONS.ELF@AIDA.CSD.UU.SE>

Milord Sam'l de Bassett, I am most impressed by your recent postings on
religion. They ring of truth and a lot of common sense - and quite a large
amount of knowledge. Some comments though (I just can't shut up, can I?):

>Just because "no such thing is known to science" does that mean it
>doesn't exist?

You are absolutely right. Science doesn't know everything, and I'm glad that
you point this out. But we must be aware that some things can be examined
scientifically, others can't. Questions like "Does God exist?" are not 
accessible to science. But we *can* examine what people believe and how
religions function. This is a field which is accessible to science and where
extensive research is being done. I dare say that most groups, sects and
dogmas have been examined, and it would surprise me if a true Viking pagan
group had somehow escaped notice.

I won't go into a detailed account of my reasons for believing that the
modern Norse pagans can't be a surviving wing of the Viking religion. That
would become a too long posting... But let me say that my reasons involve:

1. What we know about the existence of pagans i Scandinavia after the
   Middle Ages. Small groups of pagans existed here as late as the 1600's,
   but their religion was *not* identical to ancient Viking paganism. This
   is a pretty firmly established fact.

2. What we know about emigration to America, i.e. the probability that an
   authentic Viking-pagan group could have survived here long enough to be
   able to emigrate there. Considering who, when and how many that emigrated,
   this is extremely unlikely.

3. What we know of the life expectancy of traditions that are handed down
   orally in a group of people. This depends on the size of the group, its
   geographical distribution, and the religious environment they exist in.
   That ancient Norse paganism should have survived intact since AD 1000,
   orally transmitted as family tradition, conflicts with everything science
   knows about how these things work.

4. What we know of the tendency for change in religious traditions, myths and
   legends when confronted with the forces of history. Even *within* the
   300-year Viking era, Norse religion changed quite a lot. Some deities
   rose in importance, others were forgotten. New myths came in from abroad
   and old ones split in different and contradictory versions. Christian ideas
   were absorbed, etcetera. This is what happens when you don't have scriptures
   and an official, centrally controlled clergy which is charged and trained
   to preserve the traditions. The beliefs of any surviving group would have
   undergone similar change over the 800 or 900 years which have passed since
   the end of Viking times. Do you honestly believe that it could be intact
   today?

5. My final reason for not believing the claims these people make is that
   there are so many other ways to explain their mythology and beliefs which
   are infinitely more plausible and reasonable. The concept of a surviving
   Viking religion is like the story about the man who found a secret valley
   where dinosaurs still lived - it's a nice plot for a fantasy novel, but it
   has little to do with reality. Dinosaurs are extinct, and so is Viking
   religion.

By the way, Corbie is a town in northern France. My persona was raised there,
hence the name. It's not because of the ravens. Someday I may tell the story
of how Corbie got its name...

William de Corbie
