Lord Fyodor writes:
>
>Someone (sorry, I missed your name) responded to William de Corbie's posting
>about neo-Paganism, etc., with words resembling "all period _nobility_ were
>practicing and believing Roman Catholics."  I beg your pardon, but the most
>you can demonstrate to me of the above is practicing and publicly appearing
>to believe.  Persecuted groups go underground when necessary, and Pagans
>of the period would not (IMHO) have given up their position of nobility
>without a fight. 

This is one of the oldest traps in the book.  Abscence of evidence is not
evidence of absence.  That there is no record does *not* show that there
must have been pagans in high places.  It only leaves us with the records
we have--and those will show the nobility being obedient members of the
church.  The available data suggests--things like the Abigensian Crusade--
that any "heresy" discovered would have been wiped out *and* *records* *of*
*that* *destrcution* *would* *survive.*  While the lack of records does 
not constitute "proof", it becomes compelling evidence that there were
no closet pagans.  Or do you believe that over all the time involved
*every* such person kept the secret perfectly?

>As has been said many times, Polytheism accepts Monotheism,
>Monotheism doesn't accept Polytheism.  Therefore, they could even have
>been believers to the extent that the Christian God was one of their pantheon,
>but I find it very hard to believe that they were *all* strictly Catholic
>believers.

Please check on what was done (and tolerated) in Greenland after the
area was converted to Christianity.  (I will also stipulate that Iceland
and Greenland and the rest of Scandinavia later constitute one of the
most tolerant and enlightened groups in many ways and that they were
exceptions to the usual rule--up to and including the settlement of
the British North American colonies.)


This *entire* discussion shows why the Society has to be so careful
around religous issues.  It must be quite an eye opener for our 
members who grew up in Drachenvald.

