Having followed the religious discussion that has been going on with
some interest, and reading m'lord Sam'l Bassett's comments of today, I
finally decided it was time for me to put in my two cents worth (now
that I have gotten my demon box to obey my commands).I think that this
whole bit has gotten, perhaps, a bit out of hand.  I don't see the
problem if someone practices their chosen religion, if it is done in
good taste, and not forced upon someone else.  I also dont see why such
practices cannot be announced.

 Here in the the incipient canton of the
College of the Northern Highlands, our Lord Abbot, and our Prioress, and
I recently had a fun religious argument.  I, being a paganish
viking-type, was wearing a cross, and was not christian.  They were
threatening to try to convert me, and I was resisting on the basis that
I wanted the favor of as many gods as possible.

 My point is this:  We were having fun, and nobodys toes were stepped on,
  yet we were of different religiouns, and following them.

Maybe its because that here in the Highlands we have a somewhat large
percentage of non-christians in the group, due to an eclectic mix of
personae.  I think, though, that most people in SCA are similar, being
pretty tolerant, and there are only a minority out there who dislike
other religions.  At least thats what I hope.  If I cant follow my
persona's chosen religion (or best recreation thereof possible), in a
polite, un-obtrusive way, then what is the point of having such a persona?
If we end up with no hint of any religion in SCA whatsoever, its going to
get boring, and leave out a big piece of period life.

 My apologies for the length of this, I tend to get carried away at times.
