I've been following the discussion on charging for services with great interest.
In #273 (I think), Robyn (Dave Rubin) mentioned that one could get an AoA for
free, but that other awards were commissioned (that is, you paid for them).  Is
that the custom in Ansteorra, or elsewhere?  Here in the Eastrealm, things are
a little different.

All award scrolls in this kingdom are gifts to the recipients, though in special
cases one might be reimbursed (by an individual, not by the kingdom) for any
exotic or expensive materials used.  The Tyger Clerk tries to match up assigned
scrolls with calligraphers who know the recipient well, so the scroll often
takes on the character of a personal gift from the scribe as well as an award
from the Kingdom.  I know that if a buddy of mine were to be knighted or given
a peerage, that I would happily arm-wrestle the other scribes to be able to do
that scroll.  I've done such things for certain AoAs, too.  There is no money
involved at any time, even for vellum and gold leaf.  The calligraphy is my
gift.

On promissory notes: Malice basically has the right idea.  Promissory notes are
given when an award has been planned to be given at an event, but the scroll
itself is either not done, not assigned (last-minute awards are like that), or
didn't make it to the event for some reason.  Most of the time, the scroll has
been assigned and you will receive it when it's finished (or when it reaches
their Majesties; these things sometimes get delayed in the mail).  Sometimes
the scroll was not assigned, and you can take your note to the Tyger Clerk or
to a friendly scribe and ask for the scroll to be done.  The scribe, in either
case, does not charge to do the scroll.  It is considered very nice to bribe
him/her, but the word "thanks" will do wonders.

Vnend: So sorry to hear about your AoA scroll.  Quality is another soapbox of
mine, and one I won't get into here.  Please contact me privately, and I'll
redo your scroll quietly.  Unless the original scribe visits your house, no one
need ever know.  Of course, the signatures will be on the original...

To all the royalty and prospective royalty reading this posting: Please don't
sign your award scrolls in felt-tip anything!  The ink disappears completely in
less than 10 years.

That's enough babbling for now.  Thanks for bearing with me.

